<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Logical End to Constitutional Topsy- </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Clouds blotting out the
political horizon of this South Asian nation may have been
dispelled to some extent as the two-month-long tussle between the
government and the judiciary finally came to an end.
</P>
<P>
An anxious public, which have been following the event
nervously during the past couple of months, felt relaxed at the
weekend when Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif finally accepted the
recommendation by Chief Justice Sajjad Ali Shah to appoint five
Supreme Court judges.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister's acceptance to elevate the five recommended
judges to the apex court defused what seemed to be the worst ever
constitutional crisis in Pakistan's history.
</P>
<P>
The two-month-old nerve-wrecking confrontation between the
government and the judiciary, which had thrown this nation into a
chaotic situation, ended on October 31 as the ruling Pakistan
Muslim League (N) and its allied parties yielded to the pressure
of the chief justice to "avoid a collision with the third pillar
of the state."
</P>
<P>
"We cannot be a party to push the nation into the quagmire of
confrontation and chaos," said the prime minister in his
televised speech at the National Assembly Friday evening. "I have
no time to lose and I cannot indulge myself in questions of
obstinacy and egoism."
</P>
<P>
The government's retreat came two days after the Supreme Court
invoked Article 190 of the Constitution asking President Farooq
Leghari to announce the appointment of the five judges as the
government had failed to do the same as per recommendations of the
chief justice.
</P>
<P>
The mini-storm was unleashed on August 19 when the chief
justice recommended to the government names of the five judges to
be elevated to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
However, Prime Minister Sharif had been resisting the elevation
of two of the five judges and had even tried to abolish the five
vacant posts in the apex court, fixing the number of judges at 12.
</P>
<P>
During the 74-day-long standoff between the two major pillars
of the state, Sharif, who assumed his premiership in February this
year with a heavy mandate, had vowed to fix judges' strength
through the parliament while Sajjad indicated in public statements
that any move by the parliament could be struck down if made
without consulting him.
</P>
<P>
The government-judiciary confrontation was intensified when the
Supreme Court resorted to the president early this week and the
National Assembly, in which Sharif's PML(N) enjoys a two-thirds
majority, passed a resolution claiming supremacy of the parliament
in the legislative process and got prepared to clip the powers of
the chief justice.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here believed that Sharif's compromise in the eleventh
hour will enable the government to get rid of an unnecessary war
of nerves with the judiciary and to devote itself to its ambitious
economic and political agenda.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two months, the Pakistanis remained on their toes
watching this war among institutions as their official functioning
came to a virtual standstill and stock markets plummeted to record
lows.
</P>
<P>
However, observers noted that the constitutional crisis seems
to have ended but the questions which emerged as the crisis
unfolded have to be answered in order to make the system viable.
</P>
<P>
The question of demarcation of domains of the judiciary and the
parliament is very much there and could lead to a crisis of
immense proportion again.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the present government has to face the
fallout of the crisis as two important petitions have already been
filed in the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
A petition seeking disqualification of the prime minister for
violating Supreme Court orders and his contempt of court is to be
heard Monday.
</P>
<P>
Another petition challenging the 13th Amendment, which deprived
the president of his discretionary power to dissolve the National
Assembly and the government, has also been filed.
</P>
<P>
The apex court has already suspended the operation of the 14th
Amendment, or the Anti-Defection Law, passed by both houses of the
parliament unanimously early July.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the suspension of the operation of the
Anti-Defection Law by the Supreme Court has loosen the ruling
Pakistan Muslim League's control over its party members' behavior
inside the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here are of the view that just as all constitutional
interpretations have political consequences, petitions such as
these also have political repercussions with which the government
of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif has to deal cautiously.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
