<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab League Undecided on Doha Meeting: Meguid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) has not
yet decided whether to participate in the fourth Middle East and
North Africa economic conference due to be held in the Qatari
capital Doha in mid-November, the AL chief said here today.
</P>
<P>
Esmat Abdul-Meguid, Secretary General of the Arab League, told
a press conference here this afternoon that the Arab League has
received an invitation from the Qatari government, but the
group's stand will be based on the state of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to attend the conference if progress is
achieved in the peace process," the secretary general said.
</P>
<P>
He refused to make comments on whether the Doha conference
will have negative effects on the Arab-Arab relations and whether
the conference will be helpful to the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
However, he said the Arab League "hopes the Doha conference
will be successful."
</P>
<P>
The conference, traditionally attended by Arab states, Israel
and their major partners in the world, was boycotted by some Arab
states while supported by others.
</P>
<P>
Syria, Lebanon, the Palestinian National Authority, the United
Arab Emirates (UAE) and Saudi Arabia have refused to appear due to
Israel's participation while Jordan and Yemen announced to attend
it. Other Arab states have not made their decisions.
</P>
<P>
The conference deepened the split among Arab League's 22 member
states. Syria said Israel should not be given chances to benefit
from the economic meeting.
</P>
<P>
Egypt claimed such a conference is meaningless because of the
deadlock in the Arab-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Qatar and its supporters, on the other hand, argued that the
Doha conference will "give new impetus" to the peace process and
boost economic developments in the region.
</P>
<P>
Meguid said that his group has no right to impose its will on
Arab countries but will respect all decisions made by Arab states
themselves.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the importance of realizing a comprehensive and
just peace in the Middle East region.
</P>
<P>
He said that he hoped the Palestinian-Israeli meeting to be
held Tuesday in Washington will succeed, but stressing that any
partial solution to the dispute between the two sides is
"unacceptable."
</P>
<P>
Meguid arrived here Saturday to attend a UAE-organized
three-day symposium which began here today on "the future of the
Arab world and the role of the Arab League."
</P>
<P>
During the seminar, participants will discuss issues such as
Arab-Arab relations, Arab-Israeli relations and Arab relations
with superpowers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
