<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chiluba Vows Not to Allow Disruption of Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- President Frederick Chiluba has
said his government will not allow the undemocratic and selfish
forces to disrupt the peace, stability and unity prevailing in
Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba made the statement in a speech read by Central
Province Deputy Minister Abel Musonda Chambeshi in Chibombo of
the province on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Zambia News Agency today quoted him as saying that his
government was mandated democratically by the people of Zambia to
rule the country and will not allow anyone to disrupt the peace
Zambia has enjoyed for the past 33 years.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking during the official opening of the
Kulamba-Kubwalo traditional ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba condemned the October 28 failed coup, saying Zambia
does not require a coup because the current democratic system of
governance has afforded it an opportunity to change the
government through the ballot and not through the barrel of the
gun.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said Zambians know the best way of changing government
and that is through the ballot and coups only bring sufferings to
the people.
</P>
<P>
The president said the government will continue to encourage
traditional ceremonies because they are symbols of identity for
each ethnic grouping and are strong unifying force for people.
</P>
<P>
He said the government recognizes chiefs as the custodians of
cultural values and the role they play in the national
development.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba advised traditional leaders to identify, preserve and
propagate all useful aspects of their culture to the young people
who regard some of the traditions as irrelevant to modern
society. 
</P>
</TEXT>
