<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Pessimistic on Washington Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 2 (Xinhua) -- On the eve of
Israeli-Palestinian negotiations in the U.S., Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat decided not to send the
heads of the committees dealing with the interim agreements to
Washington.
</P>
<P>
Under the aegis of the United States Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, Israeli and Palestinian negotiators are
scheduled to meet tomorrow in the State of Virginia outside of
Washington.
</P>
<P>
But as result of Arafat's decision, the Palestinian delegation,
headed by PNA deputy Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen), is to include
only Palestinian Planning Minister Nabil Shaath and Local Affairs
Minister Saeb Erekat.
</P>
<P>
The decision reflects the pessimism of Palestinians on the
upcoming talks because of Israel's refusal to honor standing
commitments, and on the fact that Israel and PNA have differed
over what to be discussed and whether the talks will produce
results.
</P>
<P>
Israeli delegation, headed by Foreign Minister David Levy,
wants to delve into technical as well as substantive issues. The
former includes an airport and sea port in the Gaza Strip and safe
passage between Gaza and the West Bank, and the latter deals with
further troop pullback and proposed settlement freeze.
</P>
<P>
In contrast, the Palestinian side believes the redeployment and
suspension of settlement activities must take precedence over
everything else. They contend that the various technical issues
can be dealt with locally and it is unnecessary to include them in
the Washington talks.
</P>
<P>
Hanan Ashrawi, Palestinian higher education minister, stressed
today that Palestinian delegation will not allow the main issues
to turn into secondary issues and the Palestinians are going to
Washington to show their commitment to the signed agreements
between two sides.
</P>
<P>
She said that the discussions will not be allowed to become a
gain for the U.S. and Israel at the expense of the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Gaza before leaving for the U.S. today, Shaath
warned of a failure of the scheduled peace talks. "Although we are
aware that Israeli intransigent positions will obstruct the talks,
yet, we will go to Washington to present our point of view with
Albright's help," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
