<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AL Rejects Extradition of 2 Libyans to Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) has
refused British call for surrendering to London's courts two
Libyans allegedly involved in exploding a Pan Am airplane over
Lockerbie, Scotland in 1988, the AL chief said here today.
</P>
<P>
The AL Secretary General Esmat Abdul-Meguid told a press
conference here this afternoon that the AL would not urge Tripoli
to respond to the call.
</P>
<P>
"We can not urge Libya to surrender the suspects because
Britain and Libya do not have an extradition treaty," Meguid
said.
</P>
<P>
The AL chief made the remark in response to a letter sent to
the Arab League by the British government calling on the league to
persuade Libya to accept the British proposal.
</P>
<P>
The British government also invited the league to send
observers if the trial was held in Britain.
</P>
<P>
The two Libyans were accused of assuming responsibilities for
the explosion of the airplane, which killed 270 people on board.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has repeatedly called for the extradition of the two
suspects to London for trial, but Libya refused.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. imposed sanctions on Libya in 1992 banning arms sales
to and flights to and from the north African country for its
failure to hand over the two Libyans.
</P>
<P>
Meguid said the British suggestion could not be accepted by the
Arab world. "The Arab world will not accept the suggestion. We do
think an extradition treaty is the basic ground for settling the
issue," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meguid arrived here Saturday to attend a UAE-organized
three-day symposium which began here today under the title of "the
future of the Arab world and the role of the Arab League."
</P>
<P>
During the seminar, participants will discuss issues such as
the inter Arab, the Arab-Israeli relations and the Arab relations
with superpowers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
