<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Urged to Implement Resolutions on Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Development
Program (UNDP) has urged the Zimbabwean government to devise a
strategy of implementing resolutions of the 1995 Beijing
International Conference on Women.
</P>
<P>
UNDP resident representative Carlos Lopes today told the
Zimbabwe News Agency that the women's project would be entirely
funded by the U.N. agency and implemented in conjunction with the
women's department, UNIFEM.
</P>
<P>
At the conclusion of the 1995 International Conference on
Women held in Beijing, China, a platform for action was endorsed
which compelled all participating countries to devise
implementation strategies to eradicate gender inequality.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, as one of the participants which sent one of the
biggest delegations, endorsed the platform for action but has not
formulated any implementation strategies.
</P>
<P>
''Zimbabwe is the only SADC country which has not finalized
policy on Beijing resolutions. It is sad because there are a lot
of people here who can put together such a policy,'' said Lopes.
</P>
<P>
The proposed project, he said, sought to streamline gender
issues in different government departments' agenda.
</P>
<P>
''Gender issues should be part of the agenda of
macro-economics, population and land policy should have a gender
dimension to it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
Women constitute at least 53 percent of Zimbabwe's 12.4
million population and are the majority of the poorest in the
southern African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
