<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Denies Joint Team on Land Acquisition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe has denied reports
that a joint team has been set up with Britain to discuss
compensation to white settler farmers whose land Harare would
have compulsorily acquired.
</P>
<P>
Lands and Agriculture Minister Kumbirayi Kangai, reported to
be heading the Zimbabwean side, today said there is no need for a
joint team because the terms are clear.
</P>
<P>
"The facts are all there. The idea of carrying out a study was
refused," said Kangai, referring to the recent meeting held in
Edinburgh, Scotland between Harare and London.
</P>
<P>
He said it was not true that a joint team was set up because
Zimbabwe's interest in the talks was to impress upon the Tony
Blair administration that no compensation to the aggrieved
farmers would be forthcoming from Harare.
</P>
<P>
Britain, along with the European Union and the United States,
made a commitment, at Zimbabwe's independence to fund the
resettlement program.
</P>
<P>
"Acquisition of land is not going to depend upon Britain
making money available. We will go ahead," Kangai said.
</P>
<P>
Using the land acquisition act of 1992, the government has
been designating privately owned land to resettle peasant farmers
who were previously cramped in parched parts of the southern
African country.
</P>
<P>
With mounting pressure from the former freedom-fighters, the
government of Robert Mugabe has intensified the land acquisition
program despite criticism from the mainly white farmers who felt
they were being unfairly targeted by the government.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe has repeatedly said the farmers would not be paid for
the land, but would only be compensated for developments such as
houses, bore holes and fencing.
</P>
<P>
"The British government said they are going to look at the
legal and technical implications, then they will come back to
us," said Kangai.
</P>
<P>
He said the farmers would only be compensated once Zimbabwe
received the money from Britain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Community Urged to Help Africa Eradicate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Minister of Economic
and Social Affairs in the President's Office Eneas Comiche today
urged international community to help Africa uproot corruption.
</P>
<P>
He said at a forum of the Global Coalition for Africa (GCA)
here that Africa can win a victory over corruption if
international community provides enough assistance to it.
</P>
<P>
Comiche acknowledged that joint efforts worldwide are needed
to uproot such a social evil.
</P>
<P>
He also urged transparency among international partners,
especially when they offer material and financial assistance to
needy countries because "at times, corruption comes from donors".
</P>
<P>
Dutch Minister of Cooperation and Development Kwesi Botchwey,
who is also GCA president, said at the forum today that it is
urgently needed for African countries to fight against
corruption.
</P>
<P>
He said: "I believe corruption has become an obstacle to
development in Africa and that African countries and
international community should solve this problem urgently."
</P>
<P>
It is easy to eradicate corruption in Africa and other
continents by joint efforts, said Diane Marleau, Canadian
minister of cooperation, on the same occasion.
</P>
<P>
When addressing the forum Saturday, Mozambican President
Joaquim Chissano promised that his government is taking a series
of measures to fight corruption.
</P>
<P>
He also urged rich states to write off or reduce the debts of
poor countries so as to help them solve their problems and fight
poverty.
</P>
<P>
About 200 delegates from 32 African countries, 17 western
countries and 28 non-governmental organizations including Malian
and Botswana Presidents Alpha Oumar Konare and Ketumile Masire
attended the forum which started Friday and is due to end today.
</P>
<P>
The GCA was founded in Maastricht, the Netherlands in 1990 by
African leaders along with representatives of international
community to discuss the future of North-South cooperation in
Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
