<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS's New Chief Assumes Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 2 (Xinhua) -- A Guinean veteran diplomat,
Lansana Kouyate, has assumed office as the new executive
secretary of the 16-nation Economic Community of West African
States (ECOWAS), the News Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
He was elected to the new post in August at the Abuja summit
of heads of state of ECOWAS, to replace his ailing compatriot
Edouard Benjamin. His term will span four years.
</P>
<P>
Before he moved to Abuja in mid-October to assume the office,
Kouyate was the U.N. special envoy to Rwanda. The 47-year-old
Guinean had also served as the assistant U.N. secretary-general
for political affairs, the U.N. special representative for
Somalia and various diplomatic positions.
</P>
<P>
Kouyate speaks both English and French fluently, the major
languages in west Africa.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, Kouyate has pledged to re-energize
the ECOWAS information system so as to make it more relevant and
effective in the next millenium.
</P>
<P>
The report also expressed the belief that Kouyate's U.N.
experience will come in handy to help him survive the hot seat of
a sub-regional body, whose primary objective of regional
integration is increasingly overshadowed by endless political
crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
