<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana's Air Traffic Controllers Go on Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Striking air traffic controllers
and workers in Ghana's civil aviation industry closed the
country's air space today for higher pay and better safety at the
working site.
</P>
<P>
About 50 air traffic controllers, who started the strike
action at around 9:00 this morning, shut down the main control
tower in the capital Accra and informed the airlines that the
Accra information region had been closed, the British
Broadcasting Corporation reported.
</P>
<P>
The director general of the civil aviation authority quickly
strung together a contingent of control crew called from among
senior management personnel, the Ghana Airways and retired air
control staff, and announced the airspace was open.
</P>
<P>
The situation, if continued, could affect air traffic within,
to and from Ghana, Togo and Benin, as well as over 19 flights
that should depart Accra to other places in west Africa.
</P>
<P>
Ghana is the nerve center of the major air traffic system
covering the sub-region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
