<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Deputy Turkish PM Warns of Clash in Aegean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Deputy Prime Minister
and Defense Minister Ismet Sezgin said today that clash would
break out in the Aegean Sea if Greeks want the clash to explode.
</P>
<P>
Sezgin made the remarks when visiting a military picture
exhibition in Istanbul, the largest city of Turkey, according to
semi-official Anatolian News Agency.
</P>
<P>
However, he said Turkey wants to solve the problems with Greece
through friendship.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, both members of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO), have long been at odds over sticking issues,
including mineral resources under the Aegean, air space division
and the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz left Turkey this afternoon
for the summit meeting of southeastern European countries
scheduled for November 3-4 on the Greek island of Crete.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz's visit to Crete will attract attention as he will meet
his Greek counterpart amid simmering tensions between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Turkey started a military exercise, code-named Determination
'97, near Cyprus Saturday and will hold another military
maneuver, code-named Toros 2/97, near Cyprus Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish war games were apparently in response to the
three-day joint Greek and Greek Cypriots' military exercises in
the Greek Cypriot-controlled area on October 10-13.
</P>
<P>
The relations between Turkey and Greece have been worsening
since the Cypriot government announced that it would not give up
the controversial plan to buy 150-kilometer-range anti-aircraft
S-300 missiles from Moscow.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish military has repeatedly threatened that it will
destroy these missiles if the missiles are finally deployed in
Cyprus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
