<HEADLINE> Profile of Top Male Winners of NYC Marathon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, November 2 (Xinhua) -- John sagwe of Kenya won
men's championship in the 28th New York City Marathon here
today, closing at 2:08:12.
</P>
<P>
He bettered his previous record of 2:09:07 in the Prague
Marathon in May and last year's NYC Marathon best at 2:09:54 set
by Italian Giacomo Leone.
</P>
<P>
Kagwe, born on September 1, 1969, finished fifth NYC Marathon
in 2:11:42 and fourth last year in 2:10:59.
</P>
<P>
He was second in the Philadelphia Half Marathon in September,
clocking a career-best 1:01:18.
</P>
<P>
He also won the Old Kent River Bank 25k this year and was the
1995 Pittsburgh Marathon winner in a course-record 2:10:24.
</P>
<P>
Kagwe's compatriot Joseph Chebet finished second at today's
NYC Marathon in 2:09:27 against his career best at 2:08:23 in
Turin in May.
</P>
<P>
Born on August 23, 1970, Chebet began his Marathon career
only last year with a 2:10:57 win in the 1996 Amsterdam
Marathon, over a course not noted for producing fast times.
</P>
<P>
In September he won a half-marathon in Luxembourg in 1:00:53,
posting another career best.
</P>
<P>
Italian Stafano Baldini, born on May 25, 1971, won the third
place in the 28th NYC Marathon with 2:09:31. He is a national
record holder with a 2:07:57 clocked at the 1997 London
Marathon, a gap of only two seconds to the champion Antonio
Pinto of Portugal.
</P>
<P>
Prior to that, his best was 2:11:01 from a sixth-place finish
in his marathon debut at the 1995 Venice Marathon.
</P>
<P>
Baldini has excelled in the half-marathon, setting the Italian
record of 1:00:56 with a win in Rome earlier this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Lorry Drivers Begin Blocking Highways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 2 (Xinhua) -- One year after they paralyzed
France by blocking all highways, French lorry drivers today again
began blocking all highways in a confrontation with their bosses
over higher pay demands.
</P>
<P>
Several trade unions, including the powerful Force Ouvriere
(FO), Confederation Generale du Travail (CGT), and Confederation
Francaise des Travailleurs Chretiens (CFTC), announced the primary
actions of blockade across the country this evening.
</P>
<P>
The FO called on the lorry drivers this evening to cease work
tonight and joined blockade of all "possible bottlenecks."
</P>
<P>
France's national lorry drivers' organization, the FNCR, this
evening appealed to all transport workers to stage a strike "from
now" with "action of strength and fullness"" to make accept their
requests.
</P>
<P>
The crisis came after negotiations between lorry drivers and
the biggest organization of trucking industry bosses, UFT, broke
down early this morning with the UFT quitting the negotiating
table.
</P>
<P>
Different from last year's demands, the lorry drivers want this
time a 4 to 5 percent rise of their salaries and some other pay
raises.
</P>
<P>
The imminent strike is forcing British lorry drivers, who
transport fresh food from continental Europe to the British isles,
to flee the country, in fear of a replay of last year's blockade
which left them stranded in France for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of French car drivers are also buying up oil in
neighboring Belgium's gas stations because the blockade could
result in the shortage of oil supply, as was in last year's
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Minister of Transport Jean-Claude Gayssot said this evening
that there would not be a nationwide blockade this time and
promised to do all possible to let the conflicting sides reach an
compromise soon.
</P>
<P>
French lorry drivers got almost all they wanted in last year'
strike, including early retirement at 55, after blocking the
country for 12 days last November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-02 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
