<HEADLINE> 3 US Weapons Inspectors Denied Entry by Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Iraq today denied again the
entry of three American weapons inspectors into its territory
before the resumption of U.N. inspection Monday.
</P>
<P>
U.N. sources here said that the three Americans who arrived
today on a U.N. flight from Bahrain at Iraq's Habbaniya military
airport, some 80 kilometers west of the Iraqi capital of Baghdad,
have been deported by Iraqi authorities back to Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Thursday, Iraq turned away the three American
inspectors of the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of
dismantling Iraqi mass destruction weapons despite U.S.' warning
about the consequences.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi Revolutionary Command Council issued a statement
Saturday demanding the 10 American weapons inspectors of the
special commission in Baghdad to leave the country within a week.
</P>
<P>
Iraq also demanded the UNSCOM not to use American aircraft for
its inspection missions.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the UNSCOM Richard Butler announced last Saturday
in New York that the inspection team would resume its mission
Monday to see whether Iraq was serious in its decision to expel
American weapons inspectors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
