<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan, Swiss Runners Snatch 1997 NYC Marathon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, November 2 (Xinhua) -- John Kagwe, a male runner from
Kenya, first breasted the finishing line at the New York City Marathon
here in 2:08:11 on a misty Sunday.
</P>
<P>
This was the second-fastest finish in the race's 28-year history.
</P>
<P>
"This is a dream (which) come true for me," said the 28-year-old
African runner. He said he won because he used better tactics this
year.
</P>
<P>
Franziska Rochat-Moser, a lawyer from Switzerland, won the women's
race in 2:28:42.
</P>
<P>
The New York Marathon this year followed the same route and time
schedule of the previous ones, but it started in intermittent
drizzles. Some 30,000 runners surged across the Verrazano-Narrows
Bridge in the city's southwest at the sound of the starting cannon at
10:35 a.m. Local residents braved the drizzle, giving their support by
shouting to the runners behind the police brocades.
</P>
<P>
Kagwe has been participating the race and kept improving his
records for the past few years. He was the fifth in the 1995 NYC
Marathon and fourth here last year in 2:10:59.
</P>
<P>
At the finishing line of the Central Park, Manhattan, Kagwe said
his shoe laces got loosened three times at third mile, 10th mile and
about 23rd mile separately. He tightened the first two, but ignored
the last one and ran through the remaining miles with the loosen
laces. "I knew I could not win if I fixed my laces again this time,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Kagwe said he was too eager to win last year, but did not succeed.
This time he was very patient and followed closed the first few
fastest runners, including his countryman Kenneth Cheruyot, who kept
the leading position for the first 17 miles.
</P>
<P>
The results of men's race showed that Cheruyot was not among the
first ten.
</P>
<P>
"When has anyone in the recent past won from running alone in
front?" said Tom Fleming, who has twice won the NYC Marathon in 1974
and 1975, and is now a radio commentator.
</P>
<P>
"Winners and record-setters usually run even pace or negative
splits," he said.
</P>
<P>
Fellow Kenyan Joseph Chebet came in second at 2:09:27 and Italian
Stefano Baldini was third with a time of 2:09:31.
</P>
<P>
Kagwe won 50,000 U.S. dollars plus a time bonus of 40,000 U.S.
dollars and a Kia Sportage automobile.
</P>
<P>
Rochat-Moser, 31, is also the Swiss record keeper. She became the
leader at about 20th mile where, she said later, she could found
only male runners around. Rochat-Moser is a lawyer at his hometown
of Crissier, near Lausanne. She is a two-time Olympian and a veteran
of three World Championships. But she took part in the New York race
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
"I was really surprised. I knew I was in good shape," Rochat-Moser
said.
</P>
<P>
The second finisher was South Africa's Coolleen deReuck, who
ended up at 2:29:11, and Italian Franca Fiacconi cleared the course
at 2:30:15 to take third place.
</P>
<P>
More than 8,800 women were among the 30,000 runners registered for
the 28th New York City Marathon, which passes through all to the
city's five boroughs.
</P>
<P>
The Oldest competitors this year was 90-year-old Sam Gadless, who
ran his first New York City Marathon in 1992 and was running Sunday
with his 55-year-old son and his 25-year-old grandson.
</P>
<P>
While the men's finish was just 11 seconds off the course record,
the women's results were well off the women's record of 2:24:40 set
by Lisa Ondieki of Australia in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Wage Increase: Philippine Business Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- A leading business group in the
country said here today that any clamor for wage increase at this
time is baseless as prices of basic commodities remained stable.
</P>
<P>
"Increasing wages is probably the wrong move we gonna take
right now. It is counter-productive for the economy," said
Guillermo Luz, president of Makati Business Club which groups most
of the country's top businessmen.
</P>
<P>
Luz downplayed speculations that the continued depreciation of
the Philippine currency of peso is causing a 30 percent fall in
consumers' purchasing power.
</P>
<P>
Since early July, the peso has devalued by some 34 percent in
the regional currency crisis to the current level of 35.14 pesos a
dollar, prompting some trade unions to ask for a 100 peso wage
increase.
</P>
<P>
However, some government agencies and leading business groups
are arguing that despite the depreciation of the peso, the prices
of prime goods are stable.
</P>
<P>
"So, there is no way it (the wage) would increase," Luz said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Makati Business Club believes that average
inflation for the year will be between 6 to 6.5 percent, the same
as the government's revised target.
</P>
<P>
During the first eight months this year, inflation stood at a
lower level of 4.7 percent compared with last year's 8.4 percent.
It slightly went up to 5.3 percent in September.
</P>
<P>
Luz explained that companies could not bear higher wage
adjustment at this time, especially with lot of import content and
high interest rates. In addition, demand is slackening.
</P>
<P>
"It's hard to prescribe an overall measure for wage hike. But,
if there is a strategy of putting across the board wage increase,
it's counter-productive because it's going to make companies even
more financially difficult," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese PM to Visit Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, November 4 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto is to arrive in Saudi Arabia Saturday for a
two-day official visit on bolstering bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Embassy sources in Riyadh were quoted by Kuwait News
Agency as saying that Hashimoto's upcoming visit is in response to
an invitation by King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz .
</P>
<P>
This will be Hashimoto's first visit to the world top oil
producer and exporter since he took office and the second by a
Japanese prime minister since 1995, when his predecessor Murayama
Tomiichi paid a visit to the Gulf state.
</P>
<P>
The visit is aimed at bolstering the excellent relations
between Tokyo and Riyadh in various domains, particularly the
economic and technical ones, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The upcoming talks between Fahd and Hashimoto will center on
searching for ways to boost cooperation between the two countries
in the economic, investment and technical fields.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade volume amounted to 11.6 billion U.S. dollars
in 1996 with the trade balance tilting in favor of Saudi Arabia
by some 7.7 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Japan imports 925,000 barrels of oil per day from Saudi
Arabia, an equivalent of 20 percent of the Japanese needs of
petroleum.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto will particularly seek a renewal of the contract of
the Japanese Arab Oil Company operating in the Kuwaiti-Saudi
mutual zone oil field. The contract, under which the company
extracts 284,000 barrels of crude from the oil field daily, will
expire in two years, oil sources were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the talks between the two leaders will also
cover other important regional issues such as the deadlocked
Middle East peace process, security and stability in the Gulf
region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Competition Policy Advisory Group to Be Set Up in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, November 3 (Xinhua) -- A high-level Competition
Policy Advisory Group (COMPAG), chaired by the Financial
Secretary, will be set up here by the end of this year for a
general review of Hong Kong's competition policy.
</P>
<P>
The primary work of the group will be "the issuing of a clear
policy statement sometime next year" on the objectives of
promoting competition and discouraging various forms of
restrictive business practices, Secretary for Trade and Industry
Denise Yue told a press conference today, in response to the
Consumer Council's report on Hong Kong's competition policy.
</P>
<P>
The report, entitled "Competition Policy: The Key to Hong
Kong's Future Economic Success", is the last, and also the most
important, of a series of competition studies the council has
undertaken since 1993.
</P>
<P>
Published in November 1996, the report recommends that a
comprehensive competition policy be adopted; a competition law be
enacted; and a Competition Authority be established to enforce the
law and offer advice on competition policy, and an Appeal Body be
set up to hear appeals against the Authority's decisions.
</P>
<P>
However, the committee's proposal to enact a general
competition law was rejected by the government. "We don't feel
such a law is needed at this point of time," as it may create
uncertainties and compromise Hong Kong's free and open trade
principles, Yue said.
</P>
<P>
The extent of anti-trust legislation does not seem to be
directly proportionate to the competitiveness of the economy, she
added.
</P>
<P>
A majority of local representative bodies covering various
sectors expressed reservation on the introduction of such a law,
as well as the establishment of a Competition Authority and an
Appeal Body, Yue said.
</P>
<P>
On the Consumer Committee's report, over 110 representative
bodies were consulted between December 1996 and March 1997 and 88
responses received.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Presidents of Kazakhstan, Hungary Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Kazakh President Nursultan
Nazarbayev and his visiting Hungarian counterpart, Arpad Goncz,
today held talks on bilateral relations, economic and trade
cooperation and on regional security.
</P>
<P>
Goncz arrived here Sunday on his first formal visit to
Kazakhstan which was scheduled to finish Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Nazarbayev spoke highly of the good relations
between Kazakhstan and Hungary, saying that the two countries
shared wide prospects of economic and trade cooperation,
especially on oil exploitation, processing, production of
medicines and medical instruments and in promoting small and
medium-sized enterprises and in tourism.
</P>
<P>
He regarded the economic reform in Hungary as a kind of
experience for reference by his country.
</P>
<P>
Goncz said the two countries' cooperative potentials had not
been fully utilized and he hoped to promote bilateral cooperation
through this visit.
</P>
<P>
As both countries had met many similar difficulties and
problems in their economic recovery, strengthening bilateral
cooperation was helpful not only for relations between the two
countries and two peoples, but also in finding solutions to their
domestic problems.
</P>
<P>
As for regional security, the two presidents agreed that the
eastern Asian and the central European countries should have
security systems in their own interests to meet the profound
change in world structure.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan and Hungary established diplomatic relations in 1992
and set up a commission for economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The total volume of trade reached 46.8 million U.S. dollars
last year and 24.4 million dollars during the first half of this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
