<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF, World Bank Urged to Regulate Currency Trading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The group of 15 developing
countries (G-15) today urged the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
and the World Bank to study recent developments in currency
markets to make them more open and transparent.
</P>
<P>
The heads of state and government of the grouping expressed
their deep concern over the recent developments in the
international financial and capital markets in a special statement
on the currency turmoil issued today at the end of the opening day
of their seventh summit here.
</P>
<P>
They noted that in recent months, the stability of the
financial system in several countries including members of the
grouping, independent of their strong economic fundamentals and
solid growth, had come under serious pressure arising from
speculative activities against their currencies.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the contagious effect had spread to equity markets
in different regions of the world and this amply demonstrated that
no one country could be insulated from the consequences of
turbulence in the financial market, they said in the one-page
statement.
</P>
<P>
The leaders said "Not withstanding the importance of
maintaining sound monetary and fiscal policies as well as
appropriate measures to deal with the present situation, we
underscore the importance of strengthening regional and
international cooperation in managing such crises in the future."
</P>
<P>
The G-15 leaders also tasked their finance ministers, central
bank governors and other appropriate authorities to consider the
matter and make necessary recommendations.
</P>
<P>
This is the first multilateral backing for the fight against
currency speculators led by Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad who is chairman of the three-day summit.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia and Indonesia, both G-15 members, are among Southeast
Asian nations that have been seriously hit by the turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The G-15 now comprises Algeria, Argentina, Brazil, Chile,
Egypt, India, Indonesia, Jamaica, Malaysia, Mexico, Nigeria, Peru,
Senegal, Venezuela, Zimbabwe, and Kenya which was accepted as the
grouping's 16th member today.  
</P>
</TEXT>
