<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Unions Shrink in Last Decade: ILO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Trade union membership around
the world dropped sharply during the last decade, the
International Labor Organization (ILO) said today.
</P>
<P>
In 48 of the surveyed 92 countries, union workers accounted for
less than 20 percent of their workforces, the organization said in
its annual report released today.
</P>
<P>
The union membership rate exceeded half of the national
workforce in only 14 of the surveyed countries, the World Labor
Report 1997-98 said.
</P>
<P>
The organization's corrected figure for 1995 showed that
roughly 12.6 percent, or 164 million, of the world's estimated 1.3
billion workforce were trade union members.
</P>
<P>
However, the drop in union membership did not indicate a fall
in unions' influence, ILO Director-General Michel Hansenne said.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the study at a press conference, Hansenne admitted
that the figures signaled a major turning point in industrial
relations worldwide. But he dismissed the notion of a world-wide
decline in trade union power.
</P>
<P>
In most countries, trade unions have managed to consolidate
their strength in key sectors and enlist new members in emerging
sectors, he said. They also developed a new collective bargaining
strategy on a global basis.
</P>
<P>
"Numbers tell only part of the story," Hansenne said. "Where
many observers around the world see only decline, I see increased
democracy, greater pragmatism and freedom for millions of workers
to form representative organizations to engage in collective
bargaining with their employers and to participate in decisions
affecting society and the workplace."
</P>
<P>
In regional terms, the drop in union membership in central and
eastern European countries was the sharpest, where the membership
ratio declined by an average 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
It mainly resulted from the end of a quasi-obligatory union
membership system, which came upon the break-up of the former
Soviet bloc, the report said.
</P>
<P>
National unionization rate was down 71 percent in Estonia, 50
percent in the Czech Republic, 45 percent in Poland, 40 percent in
Slovakia and 38 percent in Hungary, it said.
</P>
<P>
The largest single increase in trade union membership came in
South Africa, which saw unionization leap by 130.8 percent, the
report said. Most of the rise was attributed to the post-apartheid
era. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EC Warns About Blockades by Truck Drivers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission today
warned that the strike-related blockades by French truck drivers
might affect business in the single market.
</P>
<P>
The executive body of the 15-nation European Union (EU) said
the blockades risk disrupting international road transport and
upsetting the efficient operation of the single market.
</P>
<P>
In a joint written statement, commissioners Neil Kinnock,
Padraig Flynn and Mario Monti said: "The commission is very
concerned about the potential impact these blockades will have on
the free movement of goods and people that is the foundation of
the European Single Market.
</P>
<P>
"The knock-on effects will affect business, especially the
small and medium-sized enterprises who depend on regular supplies
and on being able to ensure deliveries to their markets and
customers. When business suffers there is, of course, a negative
impact on employment too."
</P>
<P>
Almost all of France's 300,000 truck drivers are reportedly
involved in the strike launched late Sunday when they failed to
reach an agreement with their employers on increasing payment and
shortening working hours.
</P>
<P>
Road blocks, the number of which has reached 111, are targeted
at refineries and fuel depots to cut off petrol supplies as well
as border crossings and ferry terminals.
</P>
<P>
Under the Maastricht Treaty guiding the operation of the single
market, European Union member states have a legal obligation to
ensure efficient functions of the single market and free movement
of goods and people, while the commission has a duty to ensure the
implementation of this obligation.
</P>
<P>
Yet an EU official told the press that the commission had no
right to interfere this time because the right to take strike
action was enshrined in the national labor laws of member
countries.
</P>
<P>
The commission, according to the same official, is keeping
hourly contacts with the French government over the strike and
blockades.
</P>
<P>
In the latest development, the trade union representing truck
drivers in France called for a new round of talks with employers
in a bid to settle the dispute.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile a few key border crossings to Germany and Italy were
reopened. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
