<HEADLINE> Cyprus Dismisses Reports on Cross-fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' Defense Ministry
today dismissed press reports that there was an exchange of
fire Sunday night across the demarcation line between Greek and
Turkish Cypriot sides on the island.
</P>
<P>
"There was no exchange of gunfire. Shots were heard about
500 meters within the Turkish-occupied area," a Defense Ministry
official said in a statement to Cyprus News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The press reports, quoting a Turkish military official, have
said that there was an exchange of fire between troops in the
area of Ayios Kassianos, on the eastern part of the walled
city of Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
They claimed the incident occurred when a Greek Cypriot
soldier approached an army outpost at the Turkish-controlled
northern part of Cyprus, and a Turkish Cypriot soldier fired
warning shots.
</P>
<P>
"There were no shots either from a National Guard (Greek
Cypriot armed forces) or a Turkish occupation army outpost," the
Defense Ministry official was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a spokesman for the United Nations Peace-Keeping
Force in Cyprus (UNFICYP) said today that the U.N. was
investigating the matter.
</P>
<P>
UNFICYP spokesman Waldemar Rokoszewski said that a number of
shots were heard around 20:00 GMT Sunday night in the area of
Ayios Kassianos, in the old part of the Capital Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
"We are in touch with military and police authorities on
both sides in order to find out what really happened," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot-controlled south
and Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey landed
its troops and took over 37 percent of the island in the
wake of a short-lived Greek Cypriot coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
A 1,200-strong UNFICYP patrols a 180-kilometer long buffer
zone across the divided island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
