<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Opposition Leaders Sign Alliance Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 3 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's two main opposition
parties, the National Congress for New Politics (NCNP) and the
United Liberal Democrats (ULD), on Monday officially confirmed
NCNP's leader Kim Dae-jung as their joint candidate for the
December presidential election.
</P>
<P>
In a ceremony held at the parliamentary hall in downtown Seoul,
Kim Dae-jung and ULD leader Kim Jong-pil signed an agreement on
fielding Kim Dae-jung as the single presidential candidate between
the two parties.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the accord concluded months of negotiations
between the NCNP and the ULD on the joint candidacy, and on
power-sharing after an election win.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the ULD leader will assume the post of a
strengthened premiership in the coalition government, in return
for the withdrawal from his presidential candidacy.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to make efforts to introduce a parliamentary
government system by early 2000, for which Kim Dae-jung said he
would cut short his five-year presidential term and revise the
Constitution by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
In their efforts to expand the opposition alliance, the two
Kims plan to contact influential politicians from both the ruling
and other opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, rivals of Kim Dae-jung denounced the alliance as an
under-the-table political deal aimed only at seizing power.
</P>
<P>
Lee Hoi-chang, presidential candidate of the ruling New Korea
Party (NKP), accused the two Kims of destroying democracy and
perpetuating old-fashioned politics.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentary system would only help the collusive
relations between politicians and businessmen, which would lead to
political turmoil, he claimed.
</P>
<P>
The New Party by the People (NPP), a new political group led by
former Kyonggi Provincial Governor Rhee In-je, which was to be
officially inaugurated tomorrow, criticized the alliance for
betraying the people's mandate.
</P>
<P>
"The NCNP and ULD will face national protests because they
infringed upon the voters' sacred rights," said an NNP spokesman.
He accused them of pushing for a constitutional revision for a
parliamentary government system without seeking the people's
approval.
</P>
<P>
With ULD leader's withdrawal from the race and the low
popularity of another presidential candidate, Cho Soon, the
December presidential election is likely to be a tri-partite
competition among the opposition's Kim, former governor Rhee In-je
and the ruling party's Lee Hoi-chang, political analysts say.
</P>
<P>
Opinion polls have shown that the opposition leader maintains
the lead, trailed by Rhee in second place and ruling party's Lee
in third place, with a gap of 10 percentage points each. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
