<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> d p s 1749 China-Three Gorges-Night Scene-1 News Feature: Three Gorges Worksite at Night (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANDOUPING (Three Gorges), November 3 (Xinhua) -- It was 9:00
p.m. today at the construction site of the Three Gorges Project,
the world's largest hydro-power project.
</P>
<P>
A mile-long line of lights along the banks of the Yangtze
River, like two paralleled strings of dotted pearls suspended
in mid air, sparkled the night sky.
</P>
<P>
Down on the cofferdam, roaring two-story-tall, self-tipping
trucks heavily loaded with rocks, boulders and gravel, shuttled
back and forth against a backdrop of swift and turbulent waves of
the Yangtze by the construction site.
</P>
<P>
At the north bank of the Yangtze, engineers, technician and
supervisors of the Gezhouba Group Corp. are busy with writing,
collecting and processing data and looking into files at the
brightly-lit Three Gorges Project Headquarters, a group of
container box-turned-offices that were lined in a row.
</P>
<P>
Opposite to these offices, a count-down board indicated that
"There Are Five Days to Go before the River Damming."
</P>
<P>
On both northern and southern ends of cofferdams stand four
huge lighthouses that have been erected to illuminate the
spacious site along the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
A huge pile of boulders which, chained up with iron cables and
flanked the 40-meter gap of the cofferdam upstream, will be used
as the first batch of rocks to fill into the water current on
the day of river blocking on November 8. And rapids and swirls
bubbled and rushed downstream.
</P>
<P>
A no-man hydrographic vessel, positioned at the center of the
entrance of the cofferdam gap, floated on the water to record
round-the-clock hydrographical data and transmit them to a nearby
ship via a microwave system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> p d s 1680 China-Three Gorges-Night Scene-2 News Feature: Three Gorges Worksite at Night  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Three Gorges Project Daming Headquarters of the
Gezhouba Group Corp. is based aboard another ship anchored scores
of meters upstream. "Data processing and collection systems are
being installed," said Huang Huaping, deputy chief of the
headquarters. "All preparatory work will have been done before
November 7."
</P>
<P>
Moreover, a deluxe vessel of the like size rented by China
Central Television (CCTV), stayed adjacent to the headquarters.
CCTV is expected to televise live the damming process for 14
consecutive hours in the vessel.
</P>
<P>
Searchlights flooded far and wide to light up all roads leading
to the shores. Two-story-tall, 77-tonnage trucks lined up to dump
rocks and gravel along the river bank, so did bulldozers behind.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Jin, a bulldozer driver, who had just taken on his night
shift, told reporters that he and his workmates worked
round-the-clock in three shifts. "My shift will last till six
o'clock tomorrow morning," he said, while climbing into the cab of
the roaring bulldozer with a sense of pride.
</P>
<P>
At a slope hundreds of meters from the shore, firework-like
electric arc sparkled into the dark night sky. Workers were busy
fixing a podium for the incoming dignitaries for the solemn and
grand occasion of the river damming.
</P>
<P>
Further off, siren sounded from the vessels bypassing the
diversion channel off the southern bank of the Yangtze, a
"man-made Yangtze" designed to handle the navigation after the
damming.
</P>
<P>
The clock now ticked pass ten o'clock. It will be another busy
night for builders of the Three Gorges Project.  
</P>
</TEXT>
