<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier On His Upcoming Japan Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng is
expected to discuss the issue of furthering Sino-Japanese friendly
ties and expanding bilateral cooperation during his visit this
month to Japan.
</P>
<P>
Li met today with a delegation from the Japan-China Economic
Association (JCEA) led by a senior consultant of the Japan
Federation of Economic Organization (JFEO) Toyota Shoichiro and
JCEA President Watari Sugichiro.
</P>
<P>
At the invitation of the Japanese government, Li is scheduled
to visit Japan Nov. 11-16.
</P>
<P>
Li said the two countries will affirm efforts by China and
Japan to establish long-term, stable and neighborly ties with a
perspective toward the future to attain the goal of Sino-Japanese
friendship for generations to come.
</P>
<P>
This year marked the 25th anniversary of the normalization of
Sino-Japanese diplomatic ties, Li said, and next year will be the
20th anniversary of The Treaty of Peace and Friendship between
China and Japan. He said that Sino-Japanese ties are at the
critical point of inheriting the past and ushering in the future.
</P>
<P>
Since the international situation has changed profoundly and
the polarization trend is developing rapidly, the two neighboring
countries should pursue friendly and mutually beneficial
cooperation, Li said. This policy is not only in the fundamental
interests of the two countries, but also beneficial to the peace
and development in the world, he added.
</P>
<P>
The two countries should properly handle the problems and
differences between them by focusing on the future, increasing
dialogues and exchanges, and removing the obstacles, he said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides should expand their common ground and seek common
interests through economic and technological cooperation and by
carrying forward the friendly traditions of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said that during his stay in Japan he will meet with Emperor
Akihito, and hold talks with Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto. He also will meet Japanese people from all walks
of life, especially business people, to get a complete picture of
Japan's latest economic and technological achievements
</P>
<P>
Economic and technological cooperation is a major component of
bilateral relations, Li said, and a solid foundation has been laid
for the cooperation. At present, there are opportunities for
advancing such cooperation because the two countries are exploring
their economic development strategies for the next century.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the sides will make joint efforts to
open up new ways and new areas of mutually beneficial cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Li said developing long-term stable Sino-Japanese ties is China's
consistent policy.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that the Sino-Japanese ties will develop in a
sound and steady manner as long as the two countries strictly
follow the principles of the Sino-Japanese joint communiques and
the Treaty of Peace and Friendship between the two countries," Li
said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Chinese government will, as always, continue
to make remitting efforts for the friendship of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Shoichiro said that this is the 23rd delegation the JCEA has
sent to visit China since it was founded 25 years ago. China's
economic achievement has deeply impressed the delegation.
</P>
<P>
He noted that JFEO and JCEA hope to advance the economic
cooperation with China, and the business community of Japan is
looking forward to Li's upcoming visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
