<HEADLINE> Climbers from Five Countries Reach Nepal Peaks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The tourism ministry
officially announced here on Monday that mountaineers from Europe
and Australia have separately reached the summits of two Nepalese
mountains.
</P>
<P>
Two separate French teams with six climbers respectively
reached the top of the 7,129-meter-high Mount Baruntse via the
South Ridge route on October 22.
</P>
<P>
The climbers stayed on top for 30 minutes before descending.
</P>
<P>
An international team put 11 climbers from Italy, Germany,
Austria and Australia on the top of the 6,812 meter Mount Ama
Dablam via the South Ridge on October 28 without using oxygen.
</P>
<P>
All the teams were accompanied by high altitude guides from
Nepal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
