<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu-Clinton Summit Set for Next </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu has fixed the meeting with United States
President Bill Clinton during his visit next week, Israel Radio
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Netanyahu-Clinton summit was once in doubt because of the
reported Clinton's displeasure with Netanyahu's handling of the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process, which was resumed early last
month after a seven-month freeze thanks to the intensive
U.S. mediation.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is due to visit the U.S. from November 16 to address
the General Assembly of the Jewish Federations in the U.S. and
Canada, to be held in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
According the the radio report, Netanyahu will stop over in
London to meet his British counterpart Tony Blair before visiting
the U.S..
</P>
<P>
For the past month, Israeli officials have been scrambling to
arrange the summit between Netanyahu and Clinton, assuring
Washington that real efforts are being made by the Netanyahu-led
government to advance the peace process.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is to host the
negotiations in the coming days held by Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy and Palestinian National Authority's deputy head
Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen) on implementing the interim agreements.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported late last month that Netanyahu was
considering postponing his U.S. trip if Clinton refuses to
receive him, because Clinton's snub would be construed by his
opponents as evidence that he is out of favor in the White House.
</P>
<P>
Since Netanyahu came to power in June last year, his hardline
policies have taken the peace process into constant crises to the
disappointment of the U.S. administration, which has repeatedly
urged for acceleration of the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
During the latest crisis early this month, in which Netanyahu
refused to stop the building of Jewish settlement in the occupied
territories, Albright rejected answering the phone call from
Netanyahu as an expression of discontent over the Israeli
leader's uncompromising stand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
