<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai PM Says He Will Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh announced here this evening that he will resign.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit made the announcement to reporters before he meets his
economic ministers this evening at the residence of Chatichai
Choonhavan, chief economic advisor of the government and leader of
the second largest ruling party Chart Pattana Party (CPP), to
discuss the current economic situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit said that he had done his best in solving the
country's economic problems.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that he will make a formal announcement
of resignation on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Local media said that Chavalit today has presented a letter of
resignation to King Bhumibol Adulyadej for approval.
</P>
<P>
The Thai parliament is expected to convene a special session on
Thursday to review or approve the three organic laws governing
elections, which were introduced under the new constitution, to
pave the way for the formation of a new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the parliament on Thursday also will review or
approve the six executive decrees introduced by the Chavalit
government to tackle the country's financial problems.
</P>
<P>
However, Chavalit denied any pressure on him to make his
decision to resign, saying his departure will pave the way for
other people to take over the post.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit came to power late last year after winning a general
election on November 17 with his New Aspiration Party (NAP)
securing 125 seats in the Lower House, only 2 seats more than the
Democrat Party which captured 123 seats.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit's announcement was made at a time when the country's
economic woes remained unsolved, in particular when the baht
continued to dive, hitting a record low of more than 41 baht
against the US dollar in recent days.
</P>
<P>
The current coalition government consists of six parties - the
NAP, the CPP, the Social Action Party, the Prachakorn Thai (Thai
Citizen) Party, the Seritham (Liberal Democratic) Party, and the
Muan Chon (Mass) Party.
</P>
<P>
The Democrat Party led the opposition camp which also comprises
the Chart Thai (Thai Nation) Party, the Solidarity Party, the
Palang Dharma (Virtue Force) Party, and the Thai Party.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit this time was unable to dismiss the parliament to hold
new general elections, but chose to resign. Analysts said that
Chatichai is likely to replace Chavalit as prime minister with a
cabinet reshuffle.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
