<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Surges on Asian Market Comeback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar staged a
comeback today, surging more than one US cent following gains in
some Asian stock markets and the release of strong retail sales
data.
</P>
<P>
The currency drifted off slightly in late trading but still
closed three-quarters of a US cent higher at 71.20 US cents, from
70.43 US cents on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the local unit had benefited from stronger Asian
equity markets which were lifted by the announcement of a 38.00
billion international monetary fund-sponsored assistance package
for Indonesia at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The Asian markets also received a helping hand from buying by
Bank Indonesia, the Bank of Japan and the Monetary Authority of
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
"There was a big move in the Australian dollar this afternoon
and that had a lot to do with Asian currencies," head of foreign
exchange sales at ANZ John Reedyk said.
</P>
<P>
Helping the Australian dollar to close above 71.00 US cents for
the first time in almost two weeks was the release of retail sales
figures from the Australian Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the data suggested an overall improvement in
household confidence and reduced the likelihood of another rate
cut by the Reserve Bank of Australia any time soon.
</P>
<P>
Retail sales turnover in seasonally adjusted constant price
terms rose 3.1 percent in the three months to September to 27.9
billion Australian dollars, from 27.1 billion previously.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was at 85.43 yen, up from 84.79 against
yen, and at 1.2351 from 1.2119 against mark.  
</P>
</TEXT>
