<HEADLINE> Beijing-Kowloon Railway Line Gets State Approval </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 3 (Xinhua) -- A committee, composed of
government departments, the Railway Ministry, and provincial and
city officials, today approved the Beijing-Kowloon (Jingjiu)
railway line, a major north-south artery in China, after a
five-day study.
</P>
<P>
The railway was built rapidly, investment was used
effectively, and attention was paid to the land and environment
along the railway, the committee said.
</P>
<P>
Work on the 2,400-km-plus railway line began in 1993. In
November of 1995, the track-laying was completed. The project cost
about 40 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the railway line was an important Party and
State Council decision and will expand the country's railway
network, remove transport bottlenecks, help economic growth along
the line, alleviate poverty in old revolutionary bases along the
line, increase economic exchanges with Hong Kong and Macao, and
push the opening-up drive, according to Ye Qing, vice-minister of
the State Planning Commission and director of the committee.
</P>
<P>
Hua Maokun, a Ministry of Railways engineer, said that the
railway passed the tests of adverse weather and flooding, ensuring
transport safety and generating profits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
