<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Up On Bargain Hunting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
ended stronger today as investors bought up higher yielding stocks
and the market took on a positive overtone.
</P>
<P>
Some bargain-hunting from offshore and local institutions also
lifted the market after a choppy morning as the local bourse
grappled with nerves over volatility in Asian markets and Wall
Street's stronger close on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Henderson Charlton Jones dealer Scott Emms said some sectors of
the market were also attempting to factor in a rate cut ahead of
tomorrow's Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA) meeting.
</P>
<P>
Banks and some other industrials drove the market upward with
the all ordinaries index closing up 39.0 points at 2503.8.
</P>
<P>
Speculation about interest rates came amid data which suggested
an overall improvement in household confidence and reduced the
likelihood of another rate cut by the RBA. The RBA is due to hold
its monthly meeting this week.
</P>
<P>
The banking index finished 140.1 points up at 5171.9 with
Commonwealth Bank rising 80 cents to 17.15 Australian dollars.
National Australia Bank lifted 54.3 cents, ANZ was 18 cents
stronger and Westpac increased 27 cents to 8.55 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 246.27 million shares traded worth 746.62
million Australian dollars (530.1 million US dollars), with rises
of 593 outnumbering falls of 518.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index was 76.5 points stronger at 4199.2,
while the all resources index was up 8.1 points at 1160.8.
</P>
<P>
The gold index dropped 3.1 points to 1071.8 after the price of
the precious metal fell to 310.20 US dollars an ounce from 315.15
late Friday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
