<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vice Premier Calls for Reforms in Textile Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Zhu
Rongji has urged reforming troubled state enterprises in the
textile industry.
</P>
<P>
While inspecting this largest manufacturing center in China,
Zhu said the textile industry long has been burdened by
larger-than-needed production capacities, outdated technology and
surplus workers. The whole sector is heavily in debt and workers
have difficulty making ends meet, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said it was high time to phase out the 10 million outdated
spindles in the industry.
</P>
<P>
"By getting rid of the backward spindles, we can not only trim
the industry back to a proper size, but also promote mergers and
asset reorganizations of our textile factories," Zhu told local
officials.
</P>
<P>
On properly arranging redundant workers, the leader said, "we
must promptly institute and improve a social insurance system,
while taking necessary administrative and economic means."
</P>
<P>
"If we can successfully achieve our goal of revitalizing the
textile industry, we can say we found the key to helping state
enterprises in all other industries out of difficulty," he said.
</P>
<P>
He cautioned against rushing and said the goal should be
attained step-by-step with the phase-out completed by the end of
the century.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Our goal is to introduce a modern enterprise system
in most state-owned major enterprises in the year 2000," he said.
</P>
<P>
This goal is attainable because the macro-environment for
economic and social development has improved substantially, he
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
