<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran, Japan to Hold Political Consultation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister
Mohsen Aminzadeh will go to Tokyo in mid-November for political
consultation with Japanese government officials, local daily Iran
News reported today.
</P>
<P>
Issues of the Mideast peace process, security and stability in
the Persian Gulf and bilateral relations are expected to top the
agenda of the consultation due to start on November 17, the daily
quoted an unnamed informed source as saying.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the dialogue is a move for confidence-
building between the two countries, which started their annual
political consultation since September, 1991.
</P>
<P>
Despite the pressures exerted by the United States on its
allies to stop cooperation with Iran, Japan still goes ahead with
the dialogue, contending that exchanges of view between Japan and
Iran are necessary for the peace and stability in the Middle East
and the Persian Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
The United States, accusing Iran of supporting terrorism and
seeking mass destructive weapons, imposed economic sanctions on it
since June, 1995 and threatened to punish foreign companies which
have invested 20 million U.S. dollars in its oil and gas fields.
</P>
<P>
Oil-thirsty Japan, however, disagrees with the U.S.. At present
more than 30 major Japanese companies are active in Iran's oil and
gas sectors.
</P>
<P>
Iran is Japan's third largest oil supplier during 1995-1996.
Their trade volume in 1996 reached 4 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia to Restructure Hospital Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government will
restructure hospital management to end misapplication of funds
and reduce the debt that has almost crippled operations, Health
Minister Katele Kalumba has announced.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia today quoted him as saying in Kitwe in
northern Zambia on Sunday that short term political measures and
the lack of competent management have contributed to the
problems.
</P>
<P>
He accused the hospital managers of having failed to take
measures to adjust their expenditure to the prevailing financial
reality.
</P>
<P>
Major hospitals have continued to perform functions of primary
health care which are supposed to be handled by health centers
and clinics, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister charged that the current way of spending money is
not cost effective and hospitals are providing less than 50
percent of their expected type of service as third-level
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
"It is evident to the Ministry of Health that managers have in
general failed to take the required managerial action to adjust
to the present financial reality. This has resulted in huge debt
burdens building up in the hospital sub-sector," Kalumba said.
</P>
<P>
Major hospitals like Ndola Central and University Teaching
Hospital (debts) have huge debts and strong action is needed to
spare them from bankruptcy, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
"Ndola Hospital debt was by December 1996 a full 100 percent
of its total annual grant, UTH debt burden was 85 percent, Kitwe
Central 65 percent. Eight out of 14 government hospitals have a
debt burden of above 40 percent," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The hospitals have coped with the decrease in funding by
buying on credit, delaying maintenance and postponing
replacements and investments, Kalumba said.
</P>
<P>
The government will embark on training managers in management
skills as well as employing people who already have the skills,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"Capacity lacks in reforming systems in hospital management.
We have excellent medical clinicians but poor managers.
Managerial reforms are a must with the potential for accredited
legislation," the minister added.
</P>
<P>
The system of funding will be changed from the current one
which is based on the number of beds to one which is based on the
activities or services the hospital provided, according to
Kalumba.
</P>
<P>
He said political action is also required to win support and
overcome resistance among national interests and donors.
</P>
<P>
"Most donors in the past shunned involvement in the hospitals
sub-sector. This stance was changed in negotiations concluded at
the end of last month," the minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
