<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's First Aluminum Plant to Be Commissioned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's first aluminum plant,
the Aluminum Smelter Company, will be commissioned by the head of
state, General Sani Abacha in December or January next year, the
Daily Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Alhaji Bashir Dalhatu, Minister of Power and Steel, announced
this Friday while inspecting the facility in Ikot Abasi,
Akwa-Ibom State.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the completion of the project was
significant to Nigeria's industrial and technological
development.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the project has a capacity to produce
193,000 tons of aluminum billets and ingots per year, which is
about two percent of the world total production.
</P>
<P>
Eighty percent of the production, the minister said, would be
exported to the United States, while the rest 20 percent will be
locally consumed.
</P>
<P>
Dalhatu explained that the 20 percent represented the current
size of the market for imported aluminum used in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Another major benefit of the project, he said, is the
utilization of more than 33.6 billion cubic feet of natural gas
per year. Promoting the use of its huge reserve of natural gas is
a major industry policy of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The project will generate more than 15,000 jobs, and will
boost the production of raw materials such as bauxite, petroleum
coke and pitch, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
The aluminum plant is jointly owned by the federal government
of Nigeria (70 percent), Ferrostaal A.G. (20 percent), a German
company who built the plant, and the Reynolds International
Corporation of the U.S. (10 percent), who provided the
technology.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the project was started in 1990 and cost about
four billion Deutsche Mark. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria, Cote d'Ivoire Bid for Ghana Gas Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria and Cote d'Ivoire have
come under competition to enter the lucrative gas market in
Ghana.
</P>
<P>
Ghana is to build a gas-fired fuel station which will be
utilizing large volume of gas, estimated at 80 million standard
cubic meters per day.
</P>
<P>
A Nigerian major oil producing company, Chevron Nigeria Ltd.,
is competing with an Ivory Coast company to win the big contract.
</P>
<P>
"We want to make sure that Nigerian gas goes to Ghana. It is a
unique opportunity for Nigeria to have a win-win situation in the
deal," said Chevron Managing Director George Kirkland, quoted by
local press today.
</P>
<P>
He did not disclose how the competition was going on but said
if Nigeria succeeded, the commodity would mainly be sourced from
the Escravos Gas Project (EGP) and transported through the West
African Gas Pipeline.
</P>
<P>
EGP, involving a total investment of some 550 million U.S.
dollars, is the first major associated gas project in Nigeria
targeted at utilizing the rich natural gas that has been flaring
at the country's oil fields.
</P>
<P>
The project, expected to be commissioned by the head of state
General Sani Abacha the coming Wednesday, will process 185
million standard cubic feet of gas per day, while producing over
8,000 barrels of liquefied gas for export.
</P>
<P>
The West African Gas Pipeline project involves the laying of
gas pipeline from Nigeria through Togo and Benin to Ghana.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
