<HEADLINE> Thai PM Says He Will Resign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chavalit
Yongchaiyudh announced here this evening that he will resign.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit made the announcement to reporters before he meets his
economic ministers this evening at the residence of Chatichai
Choonhavan, chief economic advisor of the government and leader of
the second largest ruling party Chart Pattana party (CPP), to
discuss the current economic situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit said that he had done his best in solving with the
country's economic problems.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that he will make a formal announcement
of resignation on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
However, Chavalit denied any pressure on him to make his
decision to resign, saying his departure will pave the way for
other people to take over the post.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit came to power late last year after winning a general
election on November 17 with his New Aspiration Party (NAP)
securing 125 seats in the lower house, only 2 seats more than the
Democrat Party which captured 123 seats.
</P>
<P>
Chavalit's announcement was made at a time when the economic
woes remained unsolved, in particular when the baht continued to
dive, hitting a record low of more than 41 baht against the US
dollar in recent days.
</P>
<P>
The current coalition government consists of six parties - the
NAP, the CPP, the Social Action Party, the Prachakorn Thai (Thai
Citizen) Party, the Seritham (Liberal Democratic) Party, and the
Muan Chon (Mass) Party.  
</P>
</TEXT>
