<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: G-15 Calls for Regulated Currency Trading, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The seventh summit of the
Group of 15 (G-15) developing countries opened here today with a
call for regulated currency trading and fair rules in global trade
liberalization.
</P>
<P>
Opening the three-day summit, Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad, as expected, took up the currency trading issue and fair
global trade in his opening speech and described the present
system as unethical and unfair.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe, Peruvian President Alberto
Fujimori and Indian Vice-President Krishan Kant, representing
Africa, Latin America and Asia respectively, also addressed the
two issues at the opening.
</P>
<P>
"The deliberate devaluation of the currency of a country by
currency traders purely for profit is a serious denial of the
rights of independent nations," Mahathir said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir, regarded as the most vocal advocate for currency
trading to be regulated, said that a world trading system could
not rely entirely on market forces and it was time that fair rules
be established.
</P>
<P>
He said if globalization was to be accepted, there must be a
fair system of trading, be it in goods and services, shares or
currency.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia, Indonesia, both G-15 members, and other Southeast
Asian countries have suffered heavily from the recent currency
manipulation and speculation.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of Asia, Kant said the currency turmoil which hit
Southeast Asia had highlighted the need for developing countries
to insulate themselves from the whims of market sentiment and
exchange rate fluctuations in major currencies.
</P>
<P>
The Indian leader said given the importance of private capital
flows for development and the growing integration of developing
countries in international financial markets, the currency
volatility called for a new approach to regional and international
cooperation for their management.
</P>
<P>
"G-15 could work to evolve suitable strategies and consult with
each other," he added.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on behalf of the Latin American members, Fujimori said
there was a need for an international mechanism to efficiently
deal with the problem of monetary instability.
</P>
<P>
He said the turmoil that has swept the financial and stock
markets recently had shown the growing interdependence of the
world's economy.
</P>
<P>
On trade globalization, Mahathir said: "While we should accept
the removal of barriers to trade between nations, we should also
strive for order in the conduct of trade and commerce for the
whole world."
</P>
<P>
He drew the attention of member countries to the disturbing
trends that had emerged since the last World Trade Organization
(WTO) ministerial meeting in Singapore which could be detrimental
to developing nations.
</P>
<P>
He also urged South countries not to be complacent and look to
a new horizon by venturing into non-traditional markets and forge
multi-faceted partnerships among themselves.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe echoed the need to intensify South-South cooperation and
warned that Africa, which has 33 of the world's 48 least developed
countries, faced a real danger of being marginalized in the
globalization and trade liberalization process.
</P>
<P>
He said: "For most of the developing countries, the gains of
globalization and trade liberalization are yet to be felt."
</P>
<P>
Kant said future North-South contacts must reflect the credit
developing countries had earned by "telescoping structural
adjustments and liberalization within a truly historic time frame
and proportions."
</P>
<P>
"The developed countries must themselves set an example of
genuine liberalization particularly in sectors of export interest
to developing countries such as in textiles, agriculture, steel,
electronics and information services," he said.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori also stressed the need to revitalize North-South
dialogue so that it could take into account the requirements of
developing countries and enable countries in the South to response
to the challenges of globalization.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori said the priority for the developing nations was to
gain more market access in the industrialized countries.
</P>
<P>
"We must increase deeper international cooperation as it is
important for the prosperity for our countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
The G-15, which comprises Algeria, Argentina, Brazil, Chile,
Egypt, India, Indonesia, Jamaica, Malaysia, Mexico, Nigeria, Peru,
Senegal, Venezuela and Zimbabwe, today accepted Kenya as its 16th
member.
</P>
<P>
The summit is also being attended by President Suharto of
Indonesia, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, Algerian President
Liamine Zeroual, Argentine Vice-President Carlos Ruckauf and
Jamaican deputy prime minister Seymour Mullings.
</P>
<P>
The G-15 leaders later went into their closed session.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
