<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Industry Sales Increase in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Industry sales during the first
seven months of the year in the Philippines increased 12 percent
to 240.9 billion pesos (6.88 billion US dollars) from last year's
214.5 billion pesos (6.13 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
A survey made by the Department of Trade and Industry showed
today that 12 of the 21 industrial sectors posted positive with
sales value growth ranging from 3 to 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
Food processing was the highest earner during the seven-month
period with sales reaching 52.3 billion pesos (1.49 billion
dollars), as compared to its 1996 figure of 48.2 billion pesos
(1.38 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Electronics, which registered the highest growth rate of 38
percent, followed with sales amounting to 42.1 billion pesos (1.2
billion dollars) from the 30.6 billion pesos (874 million dollars)
recorded during the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The survey traced the increase in sales to the global demand
for electronic products and the depreciation of the peso from
26.19 pesos to a US dollar in July 1996 to 27.67 pesos to a dollar
in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
The biggest loser during the period is still the sugar sector,
whose sales plummeted further by 33 percent from 509.6 million
pesos (14.56 million dollars) during the first seven months last
year to 343.8 million pesos (9.82 million dollars) this year.
</P>
<P>
Most big losers were packaging materials and pulp and paper,
which both dropped by 15 percent to 2.3 billion pesos (65.7
million dollars) and 3.8 billion pesos (108.6 million dollars),
respectively.  
</P>
</TEXT>
