<HEADLINE> s d s 1516 China-Three Gorges-Dam Site Busy and Quiet Dam Site Seen Before Blocking of Yangtze </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANDOUPING (Three Gorges), November 3 (Xinhua) -- Although the
final blocking of the Yangtze River is drawing near, not too many
workers are in sight at the Three Gorges Project (TGP) site,
compared with crowds of workers seen at the construction site of
the Gezhouba Power Plant a dozen years ago.
</P>
<P>
"This best demonstrated the power of modern technologies," said
He Gong, deputy general manager of the project developer China
Yangtze Three Gorges Project Development Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges Power Plant is expected to generate 84.7
billion kilowatt-hour of electricity a year, almost 6.5 times that
of the Gezhouba Power Plant, but the manpower for construction of
Three Gorges Project was less than one seventh of that for
Gezhouba, said He Gong.
</P>
<P>
With lines of imported graders, bulldozers, and self-dumping
trucks shuttling back and forth at the project site, people can
easily feel the atmosphere that the damming of the Yangtze is
already imminent.
</P>
<P>
"Comparing with the noisy and crowdy site when building the
Gezhouba Power Plant, the Three Gorges Project site is quieter but
even more spectacular due to its unparalleled amount of
construction work," said Zhang Junfang, deputy chief of the
project headquarters, Gezhouba Group.
</P>
<P>
"However, we are fully prepared to take the final challenge,
and are working day and night to ensure the smooth damming of the
Yangtze River," said Zhang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
