<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 12:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tehran Facing Dangerous Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Health and environmental
experts have warned that the Iranian capital of Tehran was facing
"extremely dangerous air pollution" as winter is approaching.
</P>
<P>
The official news agency IRNA reported today that many
physicians, environmentalists and residents in Tehran urged the
government to take it more serious than before the air pollution
in the capital city.
</P>
<P>
Environmental experts said that due to its natural and
geographical location, Tehran faces the phenomena of inversion
and the accumulation of various pollutants in the air for 240
days every year.
</P>
<P>
This is extremely dangerous for a city with a large
population and movement of people and goods throughout the day
and night, they warned.
</P>
<P>
Lying in an area of 600 square kilometers between the
southern slopes of the Alborz Mountain range and the northern
fringes of the central Iranian desert, Tehran has a resident
population of 7 million and a floating population of 3 million.
</P>
<P>
With the concentration of social, political and economic
activities in Tehran for the past 207 years, Tehran's air
pollution has reached intricately dangerous proportions.
</P>
<P>
Accumulation of more than the permitted levels of pollution
from sources such as factories, heating devices, motorized
vehicles, dilapidated vehicles and improper fuel consumption by
these vehicles have made the conditions rife for the increasing
pollution on most of the days during fall and winter.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that at present there are 23,358 taxis, 4,260
buses, 4,643 minibuses, 700,000 private cars, about 53,000
private cars working as taxis, 350,000 motor cycles and over
19,000 various kinds of diesel-fueled vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The movement of all these motorized vehicles, has resulted in
the annual release of 1,280,000 tonnes of carbon monoxide, 17,500
tonnes of sulfur dioxide, 21,000 tonnes of suspended particles,
105,000 tonnes of nitrogen oxides, over 2,000 tonnes of lead and
115,000 tonnes of various kinds of hydrocarbons into Tehran's
air.
</P>
<P>
Experts warned that the rising high level of lead and
pollutants like carbon dioxide would leave bad and abnormal
effects on the nervous system of the humans, the children in
particular.
</P>
<P>
In order to prevent physical and mental damages in the
community, experts hold that the use of natural gas instead of
fossil fuels will not only considerably reduce air pollution and
produce cleaner air but will also save the country billions of
U.S. dollars annually.
</P>
<P>
They believe that transforming the fuel of most vehicles to
natural gas can play a very valuable role in reducing pollution
in Tehran because in comparison to fossil fuels, natural gas
burns almost without any fume.
</P>
<P>
The serious air pollution in the capital has caused great
concern of the Iranian government and the Tehran municipality
has started a project of transforming fuel of buses and taxis to
natural gas.
</P>
<P>
However, with an increasing population caused by immigration
from countryside and lacking enough budget, it is difficult for
the local government to take effective measures to control air
pollution in the capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
