<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Sentences 2 Militants to Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The Egyptian Emergency Higher
State Security Court today sentenced to death two Islamic
militants who belong to the banned terrorist ring "Sohaj."
</P>
<P>
The court today referred the papers of defendants Mohamed Fawzi
Abdel Azim and Mohmoud Moustafa Soliman, to Egypt's Mufti, the
highest religious scholar, prior to their execution, the Middle
East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The two, both on general charges of working to overthrow the
current regime and jeopardizing the country's stability and
security, were involved in the Sohaj organization.
</P>
<P>
The court also decided to pass sentences on the remaining three
defendants also standing trial in the case on December 1.
</P>
<P>
This case is the first of the three cases to be examined by the
same court this week.
</P>
<P>
All together 28 persons, all of them members of outlawed
Islamic groups, are facing charges of premediated murder,
attempted murder of police officers and working to overthrow the
government and jeopardizing the country's stability and security.
</P>
<P>
The second case is that of the returnees from Afghanistan and
Sudan where they have reportedly received military training. Among
the 22 defendants being tried is fugitive terrorist Moustafa
Hamza, the prime suspect in the foiled attempt on Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak in Addis Ababa in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Islamic militant groups are trying to establish their presence
in several provinces despite repeated police crackdowns on
extremists.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 1,300 people, mostly militants and police, have been
killed in the five years drive by Islamic militants to overthrow
Egypt's secular government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
