<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Hosts Symposium On Ocean Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The three-day '97 Ocean Law
Symposium opened here today, with the theme of "the new situation
China faces after the United Nations Convention on the Law of the
Sea took effect."
</P>
<P>
During the symposium, some 100 law experts, economists and
marine managerial experts will discuss marine legislation, marine
resources development, and marine environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Chen Bingxin, deputy-director of the State Oceanic
Administration, said at the opening ceremony that China will
improve its ocean legislation and safeguard China's maritime
sovereignty in accordance with UN conventions and Chinese reality.
</P>
<P>
China will pay more attention to the ocean economy and will
increase efforts to establish a good ocean ecology, he said.
</P>
<P>
China has 18,000 km. of coastline and 14,000 km of island
coastline. It has jurisdiction over several million square
kilometers of sea areas, according to the United Nations
Convention on the Law of the Sea which took effect on November 16,
1994. China ratified the convention in 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
