<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Truck Drivers Block Highways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, November 3 (Xinhua) -- French lorry drivers had set up
77 barriers, including six blockades, by this morning on the
highways and major traffic axis across the country as a result of
another fierce confrontation with their employers over pay
disputes.
</P>
<P>
In their strike last November, lorry drivers paralyzed the
country for 12 days and in the end forced the government to
compromise on almost all of their demands, including early
retirement at 55.
</P>
<P>
Many barriers were set up at French borders with its neighbors
-- Spain, Britain and Germany, while some fuel supply centers were
blocked this morning in Toulouse, Pays de Loire in western France
and Savoie in eastern France near the Swiss border.
</P>
<P>
However, the strikers are only blocking "targeted" transport
and have so far let ordinary travelers go as usual.
</P>
<P>
Police intervened Sunday night and this morning at two
blockades in Biriatou on the French-Spanish border and in
Strasbourg near the French-German border, with no violence
reported.
</P>
<P>
Police in Strasbourg tried to de-block the Bridge of Europe
linking France with Germany at the Rhine River and a refinery
providing oil to the region.
</P>
<P>
The strike came when the truck company owners rejected a
tentative accord on salary issues, prompting drivers' unions to
try to cut off the country's fuel supply and clog its highways.
</P>
<P>
The lorry drivers, belonging to several unions including the
Force Ouvriere (FO), Confederation Francaise Des Travailleurs
(CFDT) and Confederation Generale du Travail (CGT), are requesting
a 20 percent pay rise between now and the year 2,000 and an
immediate increase of 4-5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Transport Jean-Clause Gayssot said Sunday that the
government will do its best to control the situation from
developing further.
</P>
<P>
Gayssot promised to reduce tax on trucking industry and give
more autonomy to the trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Asia's urban water supply
situation is improving, but the region's unaccounted water --
water lost through leaks or illegal connections remains unchanged
at 35 percent since 1993, the Asian Development Bank (ADB) said in
a data book launched here today.
</P>
<P>
The data book, the second published by ADB since 1993, analyzes
mainly the 1995 data from 50 water utilities in 31 of its member
economies.
</P>
<P>
During the period between 1991 and 1995, the book says, piped
water coverage in the utilities studied increased from 75 percent
to 79 percent while production rose 14 percent and connections 16
percent.
</P>
<P>
It says that better demand management is reflected in the fact
that average per capita consumption dropped from 182 to 159 liters
per capita per day.
</P>
<P>
Better financial management is shown by a 13 percent drop in
grant financing and the average operating ratio (expense/revenues)
fell from 0.97 to 0.89, the book says.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the reason why the region's unaccounted-for water
remains high since the first data book published in 1993, it says
that only half of all connections are properly metered and 60
percent of all meters are functioning accurately.
</P>
<P>
The book calls for reduction of unaccounted-for water by
eliminating public taps and illegal connections, more meter
production and consumption and repairing of leaks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
