<HEADLINE> Share Prices Surge on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Share prices surged on the
Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times Industrials Index
shot up by 117.88 points to close at 1,703.95 points today.
</P>
<P>
Share prices started to rise sharply shortly after opening on
the back of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) aid to Indonesia
and positive comments from international financier George Soros.
</P>
<P>
"Overall sentiment is very good. Most of the other regional
markets are doing well too. Soros' comments that the worst is over
has certainly lent support to sentiment," one dealer said.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume increased to 356.78 million units,
valued at 649.43 million Singapore dollars (about 411.03 million
US dollars). Advances overwhelmed declines by 385 to 27, while 194
other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
RHB Capital Warrant99 was the most actively traded counter as
it registered a turnover of 19.03 million units. It was followed
by Hotung which had 15.2 million shares traded. Local computer
maker IPC Corporation was next with 12.61 million shares changed
hands.
</P>
<P>
NBT led the gainers of the day as it rose by 2.9 dollars to
finish at 22.4 Singapore dollars. Creative 50 increased by two
dollars to end at 42 Singapore dollars, while Buikt Sembawang
picked up by 1.6 dollars to close at 13.6 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Khong Guan was the biggest losers as it
declined by 1.8 dollars to end at 2.2 Singapore dollars. Haw Par
Warrant98 fell by 17 cents to close at 60 cents, and Wepco 500
lost 14 cents to finish at 65 cents.  
</P>
</TEXT>
