<HEADLINE> Balkan Summit Opens in Crete, Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CRETE, Greece, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The first Balkan summit
opened here today in a bid to settle political disputes and
enhance economic cooperation in the region.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony, Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis said that the Balkans was "a place of wars" and urged all
the countries in the region to make joint efforts for a better
future.
</P>
<P>
One of the major topics of the two-day summit is believed to be
the tension between Greece and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The Greek-Turkish relations have been worsening recently
because of the two countries' frequent war games in the Aegean Sea
and Nicosia's plan to buy Russian S-300 missiles.
</P>
<P>
The leaders will also discuss ways to promote economic
development and fight organized crimes, illegal immigration and
drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
The Balkan countries are Albania, Bosnia, Bulgaria, Greece,
Macedonia, Romania, Turkey and Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
