<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian-Pacific Officials to Meet on Social Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The Economic and Social
Commission for Asia and the Pacific (ESCAP) will hold its 5th
Asian and Pacific Ministerial Conference on Social Development
from November 5 to 11 in the Philippine capital of Manila.
</P>
<P>
At the conference, about 300 government ministers and senior
officials will review the progress in implementing the ESCAP's
Manila Agenda for Action on Social Development for the region,
Philippine Socio-economic Planning Secretary Cielito Habito said
today.
</P>
<P>
The conference will include a meeting of senior officials on
November 5-8 and a ministerial meeting, he said.
</P>
<P>
The senior officials will review the social development
situation and prospects of Asia and the Pacific into the 21st
century, and the implementation of the action agenda on social
development in the region.
</P>
<P>
They will also propose steps to accelerate the implementation
of the action agenda and draft a ministerial declaration.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will discuss the results of the senior officials'
meeting and approve the draft ministerial declaration.
</P>
<P>
In October 1994, the ESCAP, in preparation for the World Summit
for Social Development in 1995, convened in Manila and adopted the
Manila Agenda for Action on Social Development.
</P>
<P>
The Bangkok-based ESCAP, established in March 1947, has 38
Asian-Pacific members and six associate countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Citing the decreasing poverty rate and unemployment rate,
Habito said the Philippines has substantially achieved its social
development goals.
</P>
<P>
According to Habito, the country's poverty incidence has gone
down to 35.5 percent in 1994 from 39.9 percent in 1991, and is
expected to fall further to 30 percent by 1998 given the poverty
alleviation programs that are in place.
</P>
<P>
Habito said the coming conference will provide a venue for
reassessing the measures and action strategies and recommitting
government resources to the goals of social development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
