<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 09:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Croatian President's Planned Israeli Trip Creates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The planned visit to Israel
by Croatian President Franjo Tudjman is creating a political storm
in Israel as some lawmakers pushed to cancel the trip in protest
against his alleged anti-semitic attitude.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Ministry has said that Tudjman planned to
visit Israel next month to realize his promise made in August,
when the two countries established diplomatic ties, that he
wanted to visit the Jewish state to apologize personally for
crimes committed by some of his people during the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
But some Israeli lawmakers were upset about Tudjman's planned
visit because of what was called his anti-semitic views. Lawmakers
Yossi Beilin and Yossi Sarid, of the opposition Labor party and
Meretz party, filed urgent motions to the Knesset (Parliament)
Sunday to protest Tudjman's visit.
</P>
<P>
Meretz leader Sarid called Tudjman as an "anti-semite," adding
the president should be considered a persona non grata in
Israel. "If Tudjman does come, he will encounter stormy
protests. Many will be unable to come to terms with his
provocative and painful presence here," he said.
</P>
<P>
Beilin said it would be a mistake to allow Tudjman to
visit. "He never took back his serious published statements that
the Holocaust is a Jewish invention and his willingness to
apologize for his people's crimes does not cover up for his own,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Tudjman has long been accused by Israel of making anti-semitic
slurs in his historical writings.
</P>
<P>
Considering the protests over Tudjman's visit, Israeli
President Ezer Weizman has not decided if to receive Tudjman,
the Presidential Office said in a statement Sunday night. Visiting
presidents and monarchs are generally guests of the president in
coordination with the Foreign Ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
