<HEADLINE> Every Lebanese Home to Have Telephone by 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Every house in Lebanon will
have a telephone line by the year 2000, a Lebanese telephone
firm official was quoted today as saying.
</P>
<P>
The government is carrying out a project aimed at providing a
nationwide telephone service and install 1.5 million telephone
lines by 2000, Nadim Jawhari, commercial manager of Ogero, the
country's only state-owned telephone company, said in an
interview with local newspaper the Daily Star published today.
</P>
<P>
He said some 800,000 fixed lines were already ready for
operation and by the end of this year, one million lines would
be ready on the new network.
</P>
<P>
"All the telephone centrals that are being installed are very
advanced and by the year 2000, every household will have a
telephone line which is the simplest right a citizen could
have," he added.
</P>
<P>
Jawhari said that his company had sales people distributing
application forms for lines all over the country.
</P>
<P>
"People wishing to install a new telephone line will only
have to submit an application and they will have their lines
within 24 hours," he promised.
</P>
<P>
Jawhari said except for a 60 million U.S. dollars loan from
Kuwait, the one billion U.S. dollars project will be financed
locally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
