<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean President's Son Released on Bail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, November 3 (Xinhua) -- President Kim Young-sam's second
son Kim Hyun-chul was released on bail Monday after spending five
and half months in jail.
</P>
<P>
Kim was sentenced to three years in jail by Seoul District
Court on October 13 convicted of evading taxes and peddling
influence in exchanges for money from businessmen.
</P>
<P>
In its ruling on Kim's appeal for bail, the Seoul high court
said Monday that according to the principle of criminal suit, Kim
should undergo trial without physical detention.
</P>
<P>
The junior Kim has earlier appealed to court for retrial,
alleging it was unreasonable to find him guilty of evading taxes
for which he has never been asked to pay.
</P>
<P>
"Charges of influence-peddling to obtain money are not so
serious in Kim's case, and it is the first time that the charges
of tax evasion were applied in the court of law," the ruling said.
</P>
<P>
"As the defendant denies his crimes, there is a need for
further deliberations on his case," the ruling added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the prosecutors Monday decided not to appeal against
Kim's bail after discussing the case at an emergency meeting.
</P>
<P>
The court confined Kim to his residence in downtown Seoul and
barred him from fleeing or destroying evidence. He must report to
the court whenever he leaves the country for more than three days,
and must appear in court when summoned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
