<HEADLINE> PNA Donors to Discuss Impact of Israeli Closure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The donor nations of the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) are scheduled to hold their
annual meeting this week with the emphasis on the economic
implications of the closure imposed by Israel on the self-rule
area.
</P>
<P>
Since the July 30 suicide bombing attacks in Jerusalem this
year, Israel has imposed total closure on the West Bank and Gaza
Strip and caused serious economic difficulties to the PNA.
</P>
<P>
The talks, to be held in Israel, will also discuss the nature
of the PNA's financial accountability and transparency.This year's
discussion is seen as being of particular importance, since the
first five years of the donor-nation framework end in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Among those in the Israeli team will be Foreign Ministry
Deputy Director-General Victor Harel and Treasury Budget
Department Deputy Director Uzi Levy.
</P>
<P>
"We will try to make the meeting as professional as possible,"
said Harel."The atmosphere will also depend on the outcome of
talks between (Israeli) Foreign Minister David Levy and (PNA
deputy) Abu Mazen (Mahmoud Abbas)."
</P>
<P>
Under the aegis of the United States Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, Levy and Abbas will resume negotiations today
in Washington in a concerted bid to remove the obstacles to
final-status talks. 
</P>
