<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCA Calls for Actions Against Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, November 3 (Xinhua) -- A declaration issued Sunday at
the end of the Global Coalition for Africa (GCA) meeting urged
leaders of African countries to be transparent and responsible in
utilizing public resources.
</P>
<P>
Local paper Notias reported today that participants of the
meeting also called for an immediate campaign against corruption
which concerns not only African governments, but also civilian
society, and the business and international community.
</P>
<P>
Campaign against corruption requires a more free and
professionalized media, stronger parliament, public services and
judiciary institutions, according to the declaration.
</P>
<P>
It warned that without such an environment, the
anti-corruption struggle cannot be a success, adding certain
basic elements such as an effective legal system and concrete
measures must be established.
</P>
<P>
A free and open environment for competition would contain
corruption and make the campaign against it more powerful, the
declaration noted.
</P>
<P>
People attending the meeting believed that African countries
should take up measures to punish the corrupted, with the
participation of international community.
</P>
<P>
The meeting which started on October 31 has drawn about 200
people from 32 African countries and 17 western nations as well
as 28 world organizations.
</P>
<P>
GCA was founded in 1990 in Maastricht, Holland, by some
African statesmen and representatives from international
community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
