<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU, Israel to Resolve Orange Juice Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) and
Israel will hold talks later this month to end their dispute over
the export of juice from Brazilian oranges under an Israeli label,
today's The Jerusalem Post reported.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a senior official of Israeli Foreign
Ministry as saying that the EU and Israel have been at odds over
this issue for more than four years.
</P>
<P>
Israel has allegedly bought Brazilian oranges, extracted the
juice and mixed it with juice from local oranges, and exported it
to Europe under its preferential trade agreement with the EU. And
the South American fruit would not quality for trade privileges if
directly imported to Europe from Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The official said the EU has been looking forward to the
negotiation to be held in Brussels late this month.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that there are differences of opinion in Israel as
how to tackle the issue between the Foreign Ministry, Treasury,
Customs Department and Industry and Trade Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The EU has on several occasions requested that Israel supply
proof that it is no longer mixing the juices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
