<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran, Kazakhstan Agree to Cooperate over Caspian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Kazakhstan has signed
a protocol, agreeing to cooperate in the area of oil and gas at
the Caspian Sea.
</P>
<P>
According to the official news agency IRNA, the protocol was
signed Sunday at the end of a visit to Tehran by Kazakh Deputy
Foreign Minister Yerlan Edrisov.
</P>
<P>
Under the protocol, the two countries agreed that the Caspian
Sea and its resources belong to all the Caspian littoral states
and the legal regime of the sea should be drawn up unanimously
by these countries only.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Edrisov, who arrived Saturday and left
for home Sunday night, held talks with Iranian Foreign Minister
Kamal Kharrazi and other senior officials. They discussed the
issue of the Caspian Sea and bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The two countries voiced their opposition to any unilateral
action to explore the resources of the Caspian Sea, calling for
cooperation to determine the legal regime of the world's largest
inland sea.
</P>
<P>
Edrisov and Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister for Euro-American
affairs Morteza Sarmadi also urged foreign ministers of the
Caspian sea countries to hold a meeting in Moscow as soon as
possible to discuss the Caspian Sea issue.
</P>
<P>
In the talks, the Kazakh official expressed hope that in light
of an interim agreement between the experts of the two countries
for an oil-swap through the Iranian soil, the two countries
would improve their cooperation in that area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
