<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australians Urged to Admit Injustices against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Australian Governor-General
Sir William Deane today urged Australians to admit that terrible
things were done in the past against aborigines.
</P>
<P>
The governor-general also urged people not to ignore the plight
of the so-called "stolen generation" of aborigines who were
forcibly removed from their families in 1910-1970.
</P>
<P>
Deane said non-indigenous Australians had to confront the
terrible stories of what happened under the forced assimilation
policies of previous governments, the Australian Associated Press
reported.
</P>
<P>
The official Human Rights and Equal Opportunity Commission
Inquiry into the "stolen generation" in 1910-1970 called for a
national apology for the former policies and compensation for the
victims, including about 100,000 aboriginal children removed from
their families in Australia.
</P>
<P>
The government is considering its formal response to the
iniquity, but has ruled out compensation or a formal apology, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
"The rest of us have had to accept that in the name of, or with
the support of governments, terrible things were done in the
mistaken belief that it was for the children's good," the
governor-general told an Aboriginal exhibition launched in
Canberra.
</P>
<P>
When viewing an exhibition illustrating the story of Aborigines
paraded as savage cannibals in an American circus in the late
1800's, the governor-general said it acknowledged and expressed
the heartfelt sorrow for past injustices and oppression of
indigenous peoples.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition shows how an American showman removed nine
Aborigines from the area around Palm Island in North Queensland of
Australia in 1883 to parade them as savage cannibals in an
American circus.
</P>
<P>
After being sideshow curiosities the aborigines were studied
and measured and photographed by the anthropological societies of
Europe.
</P>
<P>
One by one they died.
</P>
<P>
In 1892, a further eight Aborigines were removed from Australia
and only two were known to have returned.
</P>
<P>
Tambo was the first of the nine to die and his mummified body
was discovered in a basement in Cleveland, Ohio of the United
States, in 1993.
</P>
<P>
There are about 300,000 aboriginal people in Australia out of
the country's 18 million population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Police Launch Campaign to Boost Image </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean police have launched
an aggressive campaign to eradicate colonial hangover still
lingering within the force's ranks in order to boost their image,
the daily The Herald reported today.
</P>
<P>
The campaign is designed to instill managerial skills in the
organization's command structure and advocate a culture
sympathetic to human rights in an attempt to improve police's
public image.
</P>
<P>
Commissioner of Police Augustine Chihuri told legal
practitioners during the 30th Zimbabwe Law Society summer school
in Nyanga of east Zimbabwe at the weekend that the efficiency of
police operations depended on the level of public cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said, "if police do not respect the rights of the public,
then the public will be hostile and uncooperative toward police.
If the rules which are there to ensure the legitimate rights of
the public are broken by police, then the public will have
disrespect for the land and the police."
</P>
<P>
"However, if the police carry out their duties properly and
efficiently, without breaking the rules which impose limits on
what they can do, the public will have confidence in them,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
"In short, police are there to serve the community and must
respect the human rights of the community," said Chihuri, adding
that police had an obligation to be accountable to society.
</P>
<P>
It was for this reason that policemen were being encouraged to
investigate first, and then make an arrest and not to arrest to
investigate, a situation which has seen the organization pumping
out money to settle suits brought against the force for illegal
arrests and detentions in the past. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
