<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Non-State-Run Economy Moving Ahead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese economists predict that
the state and public sectors will develop along with the private
sector.
</P>
<P>
Jing Shuping, president of the All-China Federation of Industry
and Commerce (ACFIC), says the private sector, which is quite
strong, is expanding investment in state-owned enterprises and
will play a bigger role in developing a mixed form of ownership.
</P>
<P>
The output value and taxes paid by the private sector were only
one percent of the GDP before 1978. By the end of 1996, they had
590 billion yuan in registered capital. There were 62,617
private-run firms with at least one million yuan in registered
capital each and 752 private-owned enterprise groups.
</P>
<P>
The recently-ended 15th Party congress came to a conclusion
that the non-public sector is an important part of the socialist
market economy. The conclusion boosted the morale of the
non-public sector and some provinces and large cities have come up
with their own measures for this.
</P>
<P>
At present, non-public, or private, sector is in the fields of
economy, science and technology, culture, sports and public health
and will have equal status with the public sector in obtaining
bank loans, developing new technology, and using land.
</P>
<P>
Some good performers will be chosen for experimenting with a
modern enterprise system and stock market participation.
</P>
<P>
The country will gradually set up a system to protect the
assets of natural persons and the interests and rights of
investors.
</P>
<P>
It has been suggested that reorganizing property rights at
state-owned enterprises makes it possible for the non-public
sector to expand its production and that the non-public sector
should improve management, build a modern enterprise system, and
build multinationals to improve its status at home and abroad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
