<HEADLINE> Namibia to Amend the Stock Exchanges Control Act </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Namibia will amend the
stock exchange control regulations in a bid to develop domestic
financial market, local daily Business Day reported today.
</P>
<P>
A bill to the effect will be tabled in parliament next year to
amend the Stock Exchanges Control Act. It would bring Namibia in
line with international practice and create new competition,
Namibian Stock Exchange Chairman Bob Meiring was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"This will allow international firms to become stockbroking
members of the stock exchange, including international banks
which are interested in the Namibian market.
</P>
<P>
"It will also allow local banks to own stockbroking
businesses," Meiring said.
</P>
<P>
Namibian Finance Minister Nangoloh Mbumba said last week that
the Namibian government had initiated several strategies to
create an enabling environment for private sector development.
</P>
<P>
These included reforming the financial sector through the
partial removal of foreign exchange control, reforming the tax
system and creating incentives for industrial development and the
creation of export processing zones.
</P>
<P>
Mbumba said liquidity of the Namibian Stock Exchange stood at
11.5 percent, higher than the Johannesburg Stock Exchange's 10.5
percent and Zimbabwe's nine percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
