<HEADLINE> US Journalist Found Dead in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, November 3 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. journalist was found
dead on Sunday at the foot of a cliff near Beirut's Pigeon Rocks
along the beach road, local newspaper the Daily Star reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The dead was identified as Michael Hall, an employee of the
newspaper from 1983 to 1984, the daily said. His body was
discovered by a fisherman at 9:30 am local time. The skull was
fractured and both legs were broken.
</P>
<P>
Initial investigations found no clues of crime, indicating that
Hall had slipped from the 40-meter-high cliff.
</P>
<P>
He was said to have been drinking heavily and carrying a
variety of drugs on him.
</P>
<P>
Jamil Mroue, owner of the paper, said that Hall arrived in
Beirut 12 days ago in a bid to rejoin the paper and had been
agreed to take up a permanent position.
</P>
<P>
Washington has just lifted a travel ban on Lebanon which was
imposed in 1987 following a series of hostile incidents against
U.S. citizens. 
</P>
