<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Supply, Sanitation Global Forum Opens in Manila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- About 250 water supply and
sanitation experts from some 100 countries began discussions here
today on the issues of water supply and sanitation in developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
The participants will discuss regional action programs to
improve water and sanitation services, especially for the poor,
said the Asian Development Bank (ADB), the host of the fourth
Water Supply and Sanitation Collaborative Council Global Forum.
</P>
<P>
The participants include government policy-makers and
representatives from donor agencies, the private sector,
non-governmental organizations, professional associations and
research and information agencies.
</P>
<P>
ADB said the five-day meeting will address key issues such as
the need for a greater degree of collaboration in sanitation
services, safer water for the urban poor and more involvement of
communities in decision-making.
</P>
<P>
The forum will also discuss ways of encouraging governments,
donors and other stakeholders to intensify efforts to implement
effective water and sanitation programs in Asia, Africa and Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
Of the developing world's 4.5 billion people, over a billion
people lack access to safe drinking water and more than 2.5
billion are without hygienic sanitation, ADB said.
</P>
<P>
It said more than 10 million people die each year from cholera,
typhoid, dysentery and other diarrhoeal diseases caused by poor
sanitation.
</P>
<P>
Formed in 1991, the Water Supply and Sanitation Collaborative
Council seek efforts to foster national and international
cooperation in improving water and sanitation services for the
poor.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
