<HEADLINE> Solar Energy Scheme Ahead of Schedule in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The global environment facility
(GEF) solar photovoltaic program, which aims to provide solar
energy to 9,000 households in Zimbabwe by the end of the year, is
ahead of schedule, the daily The Herald reported today.
</P>
<P>
Project manager Gibson Mandishona was quoted as saying more
than 8,000 lighting units had been installed by last month in
high-density areas, rural business and community centers and
clinics.
</P>
<P>
The 70 million Zimbabwe dollars (about 5.6 million
U.S.dollars) project was launched in 1993 as a pilot program and
is funded by the United Nations development program.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the pilot project this year, the manager noted,
an evaluation committee will be commissioned to look into the
successes and failures of the program.
</P>
<P>
Countries like Zambia, Malawi, Ghana and Sudan have been in
Zimbabwe to learn from its experiences.
</P>
<P>
During the second phase of the project, Mandishona said, GEF
may extend the repayment period and consider bartering crops or
livestock with the rural people as payment in an effort to speed
up the solar power program.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwe electricity supply authority and other
non-governmental organisations are designing systems to cater for
specific end-user demands. 
</P>
