<HEADLINE> Heavy Rains Wreak Havoc in Northeastern Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Torrential rains have swept
away at least four people and 15 camels in Wajir and Moyale
districts of Kenya's Northeastern Province and Most parts of the
province are impassable as raging floods destroyed roads and
bridges.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper Daily Nation today quoted a senior police
officer in Wajir as saying "we have been completely cut off from
the rest of the country. Vehicles taking food and medicine to
the people have been stuck as the rains continue."
</P>
<P>
He noted that an army 18-seater Buma aircraft was airlifting
food to security personnel at the Kenya-Somali border posts.
</P>
<P>
No vehicles have arrived in Moyale or left the town for the
last three weeks, the paper said, adding that most of the
vehicles are stranded at Sololo, Makutano and Turbi, more than 90
kilometers from Moyale town.
</P>
<P>
Local leaders including Assistant Minister Ahmed Khalif
appealed for emergency assistance, saying that people may starve
or drown if nothing is done immediately. 
</P>
