<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Issue ID Cards for First Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The issuance of national
security identity cards to Tanzanians would begin before the end
of the year.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time Tanzanians would be required to carry
IDs, sources in the Ministry of Home Affairs said.
</P>
<P>
Although Tanzania has for many years wanted to introduce the
ID cards for its nationals, it could not do so for lack of funds.
</P>
<P>
However, it has been an urgent task for more than 80 million
people in Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda, members of the East African
Co-operation (EAC), to move freely in the region with the ID
cards. Kenya is the only country in this region which issues
identity cards to its nationals.
</P>
<P>
There had been a dispute over whether Tanzania should first
pay 10 million U.S. dollars before the production of the national
cards, according to a report in East African today.
</P>
<P>
The government, the report said, has agreed to pay two million
U.S. dollars to British company Regional Services Limited of the
Isle of Man, to start producing the IDs.
</P>
<P>
Initially, the company will produce 16.4 million cards to be
issued to Tanzanians aged 18 years and above.
</P>
<P>
The IDs will be sold at affordable prices for the prospective
holders. The national passport cost some 32.5 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The East African Co-operation passport which was launched in
last April will complement the national IDs.
</P>
<P>
Since then, a total of 10,000 EAC passports have been issued.
More are expected to be ordered by the member states.
</P>
<P>
"For us the sooner the project starts the better because of
its national importance," a Ministry of Home Affairs official
said, adding that "with the advent of political pluralism, such
documents are necessary for planning and identification of bona
fide citizens."
</P>
<P>
Tanzania has a population of about 30 million, 16.4 million of
whom are aged above 18 years.
</P>
<P>
Observers say the issuance of IDs will greatly help Tanzania's
census scheduled for next year.
</P>
<P>
The country has over the years hosted thousands of refugees
from Rwanda, Burundi, Mozambique and countries as far away as
Somalia and West Africa. It is alleged that some of them easily
assume citizenship due to lack of identity cards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
