<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 200,000 Children Illegally Employed in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 3 (Xinhua) -- At least 200,000 children
are illegally employed in South Africa, local daily Sowetan
quoted Labor Department Director-general Sipho Pityana as
reporting today.
</P>
<P>
Pityana said the 200,000 figure probably did not take into
account unpaid domestic work or children working in the informal
sector.
</P>
<P>
He said this phenomenon was due to poverty, economic
inequality and a lack of investment in the education of black
children, noting one of the legacies of apartheid was the neglect
of children, 50 percent of whom were employed on farms.
</P>
<P>
He said the government was working towards eliminating child
labor. "The South African Schools Act of 1996 introduces
compulsory education for the first time and sets the school
leaving age at 15 years.
</P>
<P>
"We view the introduction of this legislation as an essential
measure to eliminate child labor," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Primary School Nutrition Program, which was introduced in
September 1994, saw an improved attendance at schools, especially
rural areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
Pityana said the Basic condition of Employment bill being
debated in parliament prohibits the employment of children under
the age of 15. It protects those between 15 and 18 years by
barring their employment in jobs where their health, education
and social development is affected.
</P>
<P>
The bill makes children labor a criminal offense and it will
be a crime to help someone employ children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
