<HEADLINE> Tourist Arrivals Up By 3.7 Percent in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Tourist arrivals in Indonesia
have risen by 3.7 percent in January-September compared with a
year earlier despite fears of a decline due to smoke from forest
fires blanketing the region, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
In the first nine months of this year, tourist arrivals reached
3.2 million, Minister of Tourism, Post and Telecommunications Joop
Ave said last night.
</P>
<P>
He said the tourists were estimated to have spent 4.2 billion
U.S. dollars in the country.
</P>
<P>
Despite the increase, Indonesian officials said it would be
difficult for the country to achieve its 5.5 million minimum
tourist arrival target for 1997 due to bad publicity over the
forest fire haze.
</P>
<P>
The fires have thrown up a cloud of choking smog, which now
covers vast areas of Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Several branches of the Association of Indonesian Tours and
Travel Agencies have complained about the increasing number of
cancellations of tourist arrivals by Europeans and Southeast
Asians due to fears about the effects of the haze on health and
flight safety, press reports have said.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is Indonesia's third largest foreign exchange earner
after textile and wood products exports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
