<HEADLINE> Large Lead-Zinc Deposit Discovered in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese geologists have
discovered a large lead and zinc deposit near Chengde City in
Hebei province, north China.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the ore vein lies some 300 meters
deep and is 50 meters thick and 500 meters long. It is estimated
to have 7.75 million tons of non-ferrous metals like lead, zinc,
and silver.
</P>
<P>
It will be able to provide 100,000 tons of ore a year.
</P>
<P>
Zunhua County, where it is located, has signed a contract with the
Hebei Provincial Bureau for Geological Prospecting and Development
on the joint development of the vein.
</P>
<P>
The project will cost 30 million yuan. Construction of
the mine will start next April and production will begin later
next year, sources say. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
