<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Buddha Statue and Its Hall under Renovation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese architects and
archeologists are currently restoring the country's largest bronze
statue of the Buddha, which stands 21.3 meters in height, and
refurbishing the complex in which it is housed in Zhengding, north
China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
The project is the second largest of its kind in Chinese
history, next to renovation of Lhasa's Potala Palace which was
completed in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The sculpture, which has 42 arms, sits on a stone base with
swords, lotus plants or various other items carved in relief. The
work represents the artistic traditions of the Song Dynasty
(960-1279).
</P>
<P>
The Buddha and hall, which have a history of over 1,000 years,
has undergone four major renovations in the Yuan, Ming and Qing
dynasties, and in the 1940s, according to Zhang Lizhu, director of
Hebei Provincial Cultural Relics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
However, previous renovation efforts focused on the main hall
and did not include the two side halls, according to Zhang.
</P>
<P>
The State Cultural Relics Bureau therefore decided to renovate
the entire complex. A number of well-known architects specializing
in ancient architecture have worked on the project since 1995.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that renovation of the brick and wood building will
be completed in September 1999.  
</P>
</TEXT>
