<HEADLINE> Peru Calls for Revitalization of North-South Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Peruvian President Alberto
Fujimori today called for the revitalization of the North-South
dialogue so that it could take into account the needs of
developing countries and enable countries in the South to respond
to the challenges of globalization.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on behalf of Latin American countries at the opening
of a summit of the Group of 15 (G-15) developing countries here
today, Fujimori also said there is a need for an international
mechanism to efficiently deal with the problem of monetary
instability.
</P>
<P>
He said the turmoil that has swept the financial and stock
markets recently had shown the growing inter-dependence of the
world's economy.
</P>
<P>
Fujimori said the priority for developing nations was to gain
more market access in industrialized countries.
</P>
<P>
The Peruvian leader said the G-15 had played an important role
in generating investment and business opportunities among member
countries.
</P>
<P>
"We must increase deeper international cooperation as it is
important for the prosperity for our countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said Peru, which had actively participated in the community
of Andean nations, also hoped to become a member of the Asia
Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum with the aim of having
an enhanced multilateral free trade system.
</P>
<P>
At the opening, Indian Vice President Krishan Kant and Zimbabwe
President Robert Mugabe spoke on behalf of Asia and Africa
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The G-15, formed in 1989 and whose members span across Asia,
Africa and Latin America, comprises Algeria, Argentina, Brazil,
Chile, Egypt, India, Indonesia, Jamaica, Malaysia, Mexico,
Nigeria, Peru, Senegal, Venezuela and Zimbabwe. It accepted Kenya
as its 16th member today.
</P>
<P>
The summit is also being attended by Algerian President Liamine
Zeroual, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak, Indonesian President
Soeharto, Argentine vice-president Carlos Ruckauf and Jamaican
deputy prime minister Seymour Mullings.
</P>
<P>
Senegal, Mexico and Brazil are represented by their foreign
ministers while Chile's economics minister and Venezuela's
industry and commerce minister are attending on behalf of the
heads of government of their countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
