<HEADLINE> Shanghai Promotes Services for the Elderly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's leading
industrial and commercial city, has recorded notable progress in
developing services for the elderly, thanks to the extensive
efforts of the local government and various social circles.
</P>
<P>
The city, one of the first cities in the country to address
problems related to the aging population, is currently home to
2.31 million people over the age of 60, or 17.8 percent of its
total population.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai introduced China's first local law designed to protect
the legitimate rights and interest of the elderly, with a number
of districts in the city establishing tribunals to deal with
related issues.
</P>
<P>
Some 95 percent of the towns and rural areas in Shanghai had
introduced insurance system reforms by the end of 1996, with 81
percent of elderly residents participating in the new insurance
system.
</P>
<P>
Various social departments and institutions have joined efforts
to provide better services for the elderly. Related organizations
have issued "priority cards" enabling people over the age of 70 to
enjoy free or preferential treatment when traveling by bus,
visiting local doctors and shopping.
</P>
<P>
An increasing number of local enterprises have
joined efforts to provide assistance funds for poverty-stricken
elderly people, with more than 600,000 volunteers currently
serving the city's aging population.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's 400-odd "homes for the elderly" currently offer over
12,000 beds.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
