<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Unveils More Reform Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government today
announced details of deregulation measures aimed at helping to
boost the economy after closing down 16 banks in a quick start on
an International Monetary Fund (IMF) backed economic reform
program.
</P>
<P>
The measures, which were jointly announced by Finance Minister
Mar'ie Muhammad, Trade and Industry Minister Tungku Ariwibowo and
Bank Indonesia (central bank) Governor Sudradjad Djiwandono at a
news conference, ranged from details of import tariff reductions,
export incentives and proposals to open the country's distribution
and wholesale markets to foreign companies manufacturing in
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Under the new reform measures, the ministers said, the
government will allow foreign manufacturers in the country to
distribute and wholesale their own products in a bid to attract
foreign investors and improve distribution through management and
technology transfer.
</P>
<P>
Although they did not give the exact time for carrying out the
policy, foreign manufacturing companies in Indonesia would be
able to enter the retail trade to sell their products direct to
consumers from January 1, 2003.
</P>
<P>
According to the new policy, the government will from January
1, 1998 to eliminate import regulations for soybeans, garlic and
wheat flour in a bid to accelerate the movement of imported goods.
These products previously could only be imported by the national
logistic agency and now they can be imported by general importers.
</P>
<P>
With the goal to improve business conditions, efficiency and
national economic endurance, while increasing the competitiveness
of domestic products in the international market, Tungku said the
government will also reschedule import duties on certain fish
products, chemical products and metal products to reach from 10 to
0 percent by 2003 from the current 40 to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
In order to increase non-oil/gas exports, the measures also
include the expansion of the program of preferential treatment for
certain export companies to cover 18 commodity groups from the
current 10.
</P>
<P>
Under the scheme, manufacturing companies with a good record in
such areas as tax payments and exports received certain financial
facilities to boost exports.
</P>
<P>
Previously, the scheme was restricted to groups of commodities
such as leather and leather products, including shoes, textiles
and textile products, wood and processed rattan, pulp and paper
and paper products, electronics, processed food, vegetable oil,
natural rubber, toys and dolls as well as fish and frozen shrimp.
</P>
<P>
This would be expanded to include steel and basic metal,
vehicle components, machines and components, jewelry, chemicals,
rubber, mining materials and plastic sheets.
</P>
<P>
The measures announced today is part of a three-year-long
reform package approved by the IMF at the end of October. The IMF
has greed to provide a 23 billion U.S. dollar financial and
technical assistance to Indonesia to cope with its monetary
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The value of the Indonesian rupiah has dropped by about 50
percent against the U.S. dollar since the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
Political and economic analysts said Indonesia was keen to show
the world it was serious about setting its economic house in
order. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
