<HEADLINE> Nemtsov: Plan for Russia-Japan Peace Treaty A Breakthrough </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Russia and Japan's plan for
signing a peace treaty by the year 2000 is a breakthrough achieved
at the informal summit between Russian President Boris Yeltsin and
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto in Krasnoyarsk, First
Deputy Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov said today.
</P>
<P>
At the two-day meeting in the Siberian city, Yeltsin and
Hashimoto agreed to conclude the treaty on the basis of the 1993
Tokyo declaration.
</P>
<P>
Nemtsov, as quoted by Russian media reports, said the time
frame means that all bilateral problems, including the territorial
dispute, should be resolved at least to some extent by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The deputy prime minister, who was with Yeltsin at the summit
on Sunday, said a wide-ranging plan for political and economic
cooperation would guide the two governments into the next century.
</P>
<P>
Russia welcomes economic cooperation in the Southern Kuriles,
known as Northern Territories in Japan, where there are no and
should have no restrictions on investment from Japan, he said.
</P>
<P>
Nemtsov also spoke highly of Tokyo's initiative to insure trade
deals with Russia against the guarantees of private Russian banks,
and described it as a breakthrough in bilateral economic ties.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sergei Yastrzhembsky, Yeltsin's Press Secretary,
told reporters that "the meeting's main goal of establishing
relations based on trust and understanding has been achieved."
</P>
<P>
Other cooperation issues not covered by the six-point plan
will be further discussed between government agencies of Russia
and Japan, he added.
</P>
<P>
Both Yeltsin and Hashimoto had left Krasnoyarsk after the
meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
