<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese FM: Sino-U.S. Strategic Ties Benefit World Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The building of the
constructive strategic partnership between China and the United
States is a new way of handling post-Cold War relations between
big countries, Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister Qian
Qichen said here today.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-U.S. partnership "is by no means an alliance," Qian
said in an interview with Chinese and foreign correspondents
assigned to cover Chinese President Jiang Zemin's ongoing
historical state visit to the United States.
</P>
<P>
Such a partnership benefits the fundamental interests of the
peoples of China and the United States and is conducive to the
regional and global peace and stability, he said.
</P>
<P>
As the world is developing toward multipolarization in the
post-Cold War days, Qian explained, all major countries have been
trying to engage cooperative, rather than confrontational,
relationships. And in this sense, the establishment of a strategic
partnership might well be considered as a new way of handling
relations between major countries in the world.
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, Qian added, China and Russia, as two big
neighboring countries, have established a strategic partnership
featured by non-alignment, non-confrontation and not targeting any
third parties. China and France have established a partnership
relationship based on the common acknowledgement that the world is
a multipolarized one.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question of how to evaluate the Chinese
president's U.S. tour, Qian defined Jiang's trip as "having
yielded important and specific fruits" in three specific areas.
</P>
<P>
Firstly, Qian said, the two countries have gained common ground
on the goal of their future relations, that is, to build toward a
constructive strategic partnership oriented to the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Another achievement is the launching of a framework on
high-level contacts between leaders of the two countries and on
the contacts between relevant government institutions.
</P>
<P>
The third aspect of the fruits of the visit is the enhancement
of mutual understanding. During the visit, President Jiang has not
only talked with American leaders but also met people of various
walks of life including those from the mass media, Qian added.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question on the Hong Kong issue, Qian said Jiang
and President Clinton did not touch upon the Hong Kong issue
during the summit, as the two sides shared the view that after
Hong Kong's return to China, the territory's economic and social
development, as well as China's economy as a whole, has been good.
</P>
<P>
The recent fluctuation of the Hong Kong stock market has had
nothing to do with Hong Kong's return to the motherland, Qian
said. The fluctuation there was normal, just as those frequent
occurrence in the New York Stock Exchange and elsewhere of the
Southeast Asian countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
