<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Opposition Calls for Strike Tomorrow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The main opposition Bangladesh
Nationalist Party (BNP) and other six small opposition groups have
called for a half-day strike in the capital Dhaka Tuesday, to
protest against a ban on street meeting and demonstration and
against police repression.
</P>
<P>
The opposition strike will coincide with the opening of the
two-day Aid Consortium meeting tomorrow, which is critical for
Bangladesh's foreign aid and is taking place for the first time in
this poor South Asian country.
</P>
<P>
BNP Secretary General Mannan Bhuiyan Sunday night announced the
program of the strike from 6 a.m. to 1 p.m. Tuesday, arguing that
the strike has been called to realize people's fundamental rights
for holding meeting and procession.
</P>
<P>
He also said demonstrations would be held and torch procession
would be carried out in each ward of the city today.
</P>
<P>
The BNP leader told a press conference that although the
government has said there is no restriction on procession, police
charged batons and fired tear gas on BNP processions in the
capital Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Police Sunday cordoned off the Nayapaltan area near the central
office of the BNP to prevent the party from staging
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
Failing to take out a procession, the BNP workers reportedly
threw
dozens of crackers and home-made bombs at the police, who in
retaliation resorted to bars and teargas shelling. About
40 people were injured and 16 people were arrested from the spot.
</P>
<P>
"We did not want to call strikes, but this government compelled
us to go for strike," said Bhuiyan, whose party is boycotting the
current session of parliament beginning Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
