<HEADLINE> India's Software Industry Worries over US New Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, November 3 (Xinhua) -- India's software industry has
expressed serious concern over a bill in the U.S. Congress, which,
if enacted, would adversely affect India's software exports to the
U.S., a government official said here today.
</P>
<P>
The new U.S. bill is expected to increase the financial and
administrative costs of hiring Indian software professionals.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is the biggest market for Indian software exports. The
increased burden placed on a U.S. company when hiring an Indian
professional would hamper the free flow of software trade between
India and the U.S., he said.
</P>
<P>
"The bill, seeking to amend the Immigration and Nationality Act
of the U.S., is discriminatory in nature as it tries to
differentiate between an Indian and a U.S. employee. India's
competitive advantage in software would be stifled by this kind of
non-tariff barriers being put up by developed countries," he said.
</P>
