<HEADLINE> Thai Tourism Society Offers Guidelines Against Baht </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The Thailand Tourism Society
has provided pricing guidelines for hotel and tour operators as
the country faces continued currency fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
According to the guidelines issued by the non-government
tourism grouping, local hotel and tour operators are urged to use
the baht as the main currency in a deal unless it is agreed by
partners to use other currencies.
</P>
<P>
The society comprising Thailand's eight major tourism
organizations also suggested that Thai hotel and tour operators
adjust prices in line with inflation or currency fluctuations if
the Thai economy worsens in the future.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the society called on local tour operators to
maintain their existing contracts, despite the impacts of the
currency fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers said that most Thai hotel and tour operators
have changed their price quotations to foreign travel agents after
the baht floated on July 2 this year.
</P>
<P>
Worrying about foreign-exchange losses, most Thai hotel and
tour operators adopted a wait-and-see attitude in view of the baht
depreciation before offering new packages to overseas agents,
which have blocked more tourists from visiting Thailand in the
high season.
</P>
<P>
The society warned that the suspension of some contracts may
hurt the country's tourism significantly.
</P>
<P>
The baht continued to decline last weekend, plunging to a
record low of more than 41 baht against the U.S. dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
