<HEADLINE> Dhaka Asks Society to Help Eradicate Blindness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Minister of Health
and Family Welfare Salahuddin Yusuf has urged workers of the
voluntary organizations to work dedicatedly to satisfy the huge
demand for blood and eradicate blindness from the country by
expanding their activities, a local newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
"We need a coordinated program to ensure the removal of
blindness from society and supply of pure blood to the patients,"
the Bangladesh Observer quoted the minister as saying while
inaugurating the National Voluntary Blood Donation and Posthumous
Eye Donation Day '97 in Dhaka Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The yearly demand for blood in the country is about 250,000
units, of which 50,000 units are supplied after collection from
the donors, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that blood is also being collected by Lions Club
and Red Crescent Society, and the blood also comes from
professional donors, most of whom are suffering from different
killer diseases.
</P>
<P>
"We can turn the blind people into active citizens by
transplanting cornea timely," the minister said. "For this, we
need modern eye-banks and a huge number of cornea which could be
made available through voluntary eye donation program."
</P>
<P>
He also emphasized the need for developing and modernizing the
blood banks for the country and preventing professional blood
donation.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh has a great many voluntary blood donors and
volunteers, the minister said, adding "Now what we need is a
coordinated program."
</P>
<P>
He said that there is no religious bar to eye or blood
donation, rather all the religions have encouraged it.
</P>
<P>
The health sector was seriously neglected by the governments of
last 21 years, the minister noted, adding that as a result, the
rich of the country go abroad for better treatment and spend a
large amount of money every year.
</P>
<P>
The government will allocate enough money for expanding the
activities in such fields, he said. 
</P>
