<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S'pore Monetary Authority Intervenes in Forex Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The Monetary Authority of
Singapore (MAS), acting in concert with Bank of Indonesia and the
Bank of Japan, intervened in the Singapore foreign exchange market
today, buying Indonesian rupiah against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
In his statement, Finance Minister Richard Hu said that
Singapore's participation in this joint intervention "reflects our
confidence in the macroeconomic policies of the Indonesian
government".
</P>
<P>
The international community announced plans last Friday to get
Indonesia's economy back on track, offering it an almost 40
billion U.S. dollars aid package. The IMF (International Monetary
Fund) was ready to step in with 10 billion U.S. dollars over three
years provided Indonesia met the terms of a comprehensive reform
package.
</P>
<P>
"Singapore supports the Indonesian government's decision to
implement the policy program formulated with the IMF, World Bank
and ADB (Asian Development Bank)," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister declared that the depreciation of the rupiah in
recent months is excessive. "Today's joint intervention is aimed
at promoting a strengthening of the rupiah to levels more
consistent with the fundamentals of the Indonesian economy," he
stressed, but gave no details as to how large the size of the
concerted intervention was.
</P>
<P>
"Singapore shares the view of Indonesia and Japan that rupiah
stabilization is necessary for the success of the policy program.
With this in mind, the three monetary authorities stand ready to
act again, as and when necessary, in the future," he added.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Japanese Finance Minister Hiroshi Mitsuzuka
said in his statement that the Bank of Japan operated in the
Singapore foreign exchange market today on behalf of the Ministry
of Finance, in concert with the Indonesian and Singaporean
monetary authorities.
</P>
<P>
"This operation is aimed at correcting excessive depreciation
of the Indonesian rupiah," he said, adding that he "firmly"
believed that the operation should contribute to stabilizing the
Indonesian economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
