<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Rice Export Revenue to Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is expected to earn up
to 51 billion baht (1.2 billion U.S. dollars) from rice exports
this year, with a year-on-year increase of 10 percent, according
to statistics from the Foreign Trade Department.
</P>
<P>
In the first nine months of this year, Thailand exported 3.92
million tons of rice worth 43.1 billion baht (1.07 billion
dollars), with an 8 percent drop in volume but a 10.3 percent rise
in value over the same period of last year, a press report said
today.
</P>
<P>
The department expected rice exports to continue to rise in the
last quarter of this year to bring the year's total exports to
nearly 5 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Buyers of Thai rice included Iraq, which was permitted by the
United Nations to import more rice under the second round of an
oil for food scheme, and Indonesia, which was importing more Thai
rice after suffering a drought brought by the El Nino phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
El Nino has caused drought and heavy floods in plantations in
many other countries, which has led to higher rice prices.
</P>
<P>
Next year, Thailand is forecast to produce a total of 20.6
million tons of paddy from two crops.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
