<HEADLINE> Showcase for Equipment Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANDOUPING (Three Gorges), November 3 (Xinhua) -- At a first
glimpse of the 15.28 sq km dam site of the Three Gorges Project,
reporters were most impressed by a long line of self-dumping
trucks with heavy loads of rocks and gravel shuttling back and
forth on its cofferdam.
</P>
<P>
These huge "Yellow Ducks," as construction workers of the
project call them, are a batch of heavy-duty, self-tipping trucks
made by the Caterpillar company, a U.S. firm. And they constitute
only a small part of the construction machinery imported to use in
the Three Gorges Project.
</P>
<P>
According to Liu Youjiang, deputy chief of the Three Gorges
Project Headquarters under the Gezhouba Share-Holding Group, his
project, as the world's largest water control project, has drawn
worldwide attention from the very start, which finally evolved
into increasing competitions and active participation by
international manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
Since one third of the project's investment, or more than 8.43
billion US dollars, will be used for purchase of construction
materials and equipment. The project held three international
biddings for equipment purchase last year alone, valued at 135
million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The fierce competitions and golden opportunity have been
displayed in the massive cumulation of various machinery imports
at the dam site, which Liu described as "a showcase for modern
equipment".
</P>
<P>
"More than half of the machinery equipment put to use at the
project site has been imported," said Liu, adding that the
collection of imported machinery also include US-made vibration
drum-type roller and bulldozers, big-horse power Sweden hydraulic
rigs, Japanese concrete producing equipment, and German
excavators.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges Project has created a huge demand for the
world's most advanced construction equipment, since it was labeled
as the biggest water control project, involving the most
complicated technologies, according to the deputy chief engineer
of the China Yangtze Three Gorges Project Development Corporation
Deng Jinglong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
