<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Initiates Project to Revitalize Plantation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government has
initiated a project to revitalize its plantation sector with
assistance from the Asian Development Bank (ADB) and Japan's
Overseas Economic Cooperation Fund (OECF), official sources said
here today.
</P>
<P>
A sum of 1 billion rupees (17 million U.S. dollars) has been
approved as long term financial support to 10 plantation companies
under the initiative, a spokesman for the Plantation Restructuring
Project (PRP) said.
</P>
<P>
He said the injection of long-term concessionary capital would
be an effective means to revitalize the plantation sector and make
it competitive.
</P>
<P>
The fund will be invested primarily in field development,
processing activities and human resources and social welfare
development.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman added that most of the approved fund would be
invested in field development which involves replanting,
in-filling, upkeep of immature plantations and value-adding
diversification into other areas such as dairy farming and
floriculture.
</P>
<P>
The ADB and the OECF have decided to provide a fund of 80
million dollars over a five-year period for the project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
