<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN to Send Mission to Iraq to Resolve Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The Secretary-General of
the United Nations Kofi Annan decided today to sent a mission
to Iraq to persuade the Iraqi Government to reverse its decision
on banning Americans taking part in UN weapons inspections,
according to UN spokesman's office.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman's office said in a statement, "The
Secretary-General is deeply concerned about the potentially grave
consequences of the decision announced by the Government of Iraq
on October 29 concerning implementation of the Security Council
resolutions governing the elimination of Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction."
</P>
<P>
Iraq's ban is widely seen as the response to a resolution
adopted by the U.N. Security Council last month threatening a ban
on travel abroad by Iraqi officials who interfered with the work
of U.N. inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The mission would be composed of three: Lakhdar Brahimi of
Algerian, Emilio Cardenas from Argentina and Jan Eliasson from
Sweden, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Richard Butler, head of the arms inspectors, said after
briefing the Security Council on Friday that he would order his
experts to resume inspections on Monday which had been halted
after Iraq announced the ban. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
