<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four billion Yuan for Tibet Highway System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government plans to
allocate four billion yuan (480 million US dollars) over the next
20 years to construct and improve highways in the Tibet Autonomous
Region, the southwest China region known as the "Roof of the
World".
</P>
<P>
Tibet, located at a high altitude prone to severe weather
conditions, is the only region in China without a railway
system. Highways therefore plays an extremely important role in
the region's economic construction.
</P>
<P>
The region plans to build or improve highways stretching a
total of 10,000 kilometers. The highway system will link most
parts of the region and will provide access to neighboring Yunnan,
Qinghai and Sichuan provinces and the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region.
</P>
<P>
The region will improve a number of existing highways,
including the Qinghai-Tibet and Sichuan-Tibet highways, by the
year 2000. Related projects will involve blacktopping gravel roads
and consolidating slope protection.
</P>
<P>
The central government has allocated over four billion yuan
(480 million dollars) for highway construction in Tibet over the
past 40 years, with roads stretching 22,300 km currently linking
77 percent of the counties in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
