<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Government to Launch Campaign to Bolster Image </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government will launch
a public relations campaign on state-run radio stations in a bid
to bolster its image and boost confidence in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The move came as Democrats and business groups stepped up
pressure on the Chart Pattana Party (CPP), the key coalition
partner, to pull out of the coalition to force Prime Minister
Chavalit Yongchaiyudh to resign, the Bangkok Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government's public relations effort will involve
three- to five-minute "news" segments after the morning news on
Tuesdays and Fridays to allow the administration to give its side
of the story, deputy government spokeswoman Kanala Kanthaprab was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's piece will announce what is to be discussed at the
day's cabinet meeting while the Friday broadcast will feature a
weekly news wrap-up. The first broadcast will be aired on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Kanala said the news segments would be factual in detail and
presented in a straightforward manner.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government has blamed the media for exacerbating the
economic crisis in Thailand and scaring away investors by
publishing inaccurate reports.
</P>
<P>
The spokeswoman said political stability was needed to restore
confidence in the economy and the government should not have to
take all the blame for what was going wrong.
</P>
<P>
Democrats and business groups want the CPP to withdraw to force
Chavalit Yongchaiyudh to resign, in what they say is a last-ditch
effort to save Thailand from economic ruin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
