<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Government to Consider Rebel Peace Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The Colombian
government today agreed to study a peace proposal put forward by
one of the two rebel groups still fighting the country's civil war.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Maria Emma Mejia said the government would
study the plan from the National Liberation Army (ELN), which is
headed by former Spanish Roman Catholic priest Manuel Perez.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, however, Mejia also criticized the ELN's latest
kidnapping, on October 23, of two foreign election observers and a
Colombian human rights official working with the two.
</P>
<P>
The ELN released the three hostages on Saturday and proposed in
the same day a national peace convention as a step toward ending
decades of fighting in this Central American nation.
</P>
<P>
Such a convention, the rebel group said, would "give political
space to those who are always forgotten and take a step toward a
constituent assembly to elect a new government."
</P>
<P>
The ELN proposal is similar to one made by the Revolutionary
Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC), which is the older and stronger
of the two guerrilla groups in Colombia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
