<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Trade Booming in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Foreign trade has emerged as
the primary catalyst enabling Shanghai, China's largest
metropolitan area, to enjoy rapid economic development and expand
international markets.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, the city's export volume has grown by an average
18.2 percent annually and currently stands at 8.8 billion
U.S. dollars, with imports growing by 31.4 percent to 6.8 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Experts note the importance for the coordinated development of
foreign trade in goods, technology and services. For example, the
city's technology exports in 1996 increased to 537 million
U.S. dollars from 249 million U.S. dollars in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has established trade ties with 205 countries and
regions. The city has also established more than 400 enterprises
in over 50 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Pudong, the city's new development zone, exported products
valued at 2.7 billion U.S. dollars in 1996, accounting for 20.4
percent of the city's total export volume.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai Municipal government has mapped out new plans to
increase the city's export volume to 20 billion U.S. dollars in
the year 2000, a rise of 50 percent over 1996.
</P>
<P>
The municipality is actively opening new overseas markets in
Southeast Asia, the Middle East and Oceania, including Australia
and New Zealand. It is also expanding traditional markets in
Japan, the United States, Hong Kong and Macao. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
