<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prodi: Italy's Welfare Plan Not Perfect, But Big Step Ahead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, November 2 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government's welfare
reform package may not be perfect, but it represents a big step
forward towards the proposed European economic and monetary union,
Prime Minister Romano Prodi said today.
</P>
<P>
Prodi made the remarks at Bologna, his home town, when commenting
an agreement reached between the Italian government and trade
unions on Saturday to save an equivalent of about 2.3 billion
U.S. dollars from the national pension program.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that people could criticize the reform "for not
having done everything, but reforms are made step by step and in
this case enormous progress has been made" to secure Italy's entry
into the European Economic and Monetary Union (EMU) slated for 1999.
</P>
<P>
On the pension reform, Prodi noted, "we have strongly unified
the Italian pension system. We have not made it perfect, but
reforms are made step by step, with the nation behind them and
above all in the right direction."
</P>
<P>
"The pension system, which was very unjust, is now more fair,
thanks to modifying the higher pensions, taking away certain
privileges and eliminating certain special systems," he said.
</P>
<P>
The government must now reach an agreement with the independent
unions which should also contribute to readjusting the pension
system, said the prime minister. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
