<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Oil, Gas Field Found in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, November 3 (Xinhua) -- One more new oil and natural gas
field has been discovered off Myanmar's Tanintharyi coast.
</P>
<P>
Official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar today quoted a
report of the Ministry of Energy as saying that the new well, Aung
Zeya Test Well, is located within block M-12, 320 kilometers west
of Dawei of Tanintharyi division and 40 kilometers northwest of
Yetagun offshore natural gas field being developed.
</P>
<P>
The well, from which oil and natural gas can be extracted on a
commercial scale, has been drilled down to 3.716 kilometers since
September by the Texaco Exploration Myanmar Inc. of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. company has been jointly developing Myanmar's Yetagun
gas field in partnership with the PTTEP (Thailand), Premier
(Britain), Nippon (Japan) and MOGE (Myanmar). Natural gas from the
field will be exported to Thailand beginning 1999, according to a
contract signed in March between the Petroleum Authority of
Thailand and the developers.
</P>
<P>
Texaco is also conducting drilling at another test well, the
Aunglaba, of the same block.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, altogether six U.S. companies
including the ARCO, Texaco and UNOCAL are involved in oil and
natural gas exploration in Myanmar, in addition to those from
Australia, Britain, France, Indonesia, Japan, Malaysia and
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The statistics also show that foreign investment in Myanmar's
oil and gas sector had reached 2.295 billion U.S. dollars in 45
permitted projects by the end of September this year.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment in Myanmar totaled 6.44 billion U.S.
dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
