<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank Syndicate to Provide Loan for GM Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, November 3 (Xinhua) -- A banking syndicate consisting
of nine major Chinese and overseas banks in Shanghai, China's
largest financial and trade city, is expected to loan 821 million
US dollars to China's largest automobile manufacturing project.
</P>
<P>
The syndicate will coordinate funding for the Shanghai General
Motors Co. Ltd. (SGM), a major Sino-US venture involving total
investments of 1.52 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The project will have an annual production capacity of 50,000
luxury sedans by the year of 2000, with plans calling for the
annual output to hit 100,000 by 2003.
</P>
<P>
SGM will use the syndicated loan to purchase production
equipment and engineering and technological services abroad,
according to bank officials.
</P>
<P>
U.S-based Citibank, heading a group of eight foreign banks
including Chase Manhattan Bank, Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank, Bank of
America, Deutsche Bank, Standard Chartered Bank and ING Societe
Generale, will underwrite total loans of 550 million US dollars
for SGM. The remaining bank, the Finance Co., a subsidiary of the
Shanghai Automotive Industry Corp., will underwrite loans of 220
million US dollars in Renminbi yuan from Chinese banks, including
the Shanghai branches of Industrial and Commercial Bank of China,
Bank of China, China Construction Bank, Communications Bank of
China, Investment Bank of China, and several new Chinese banks.
</P>
<P>
SGM was jointly established by General Motors and two Chinese
partners --Shanghai Automotive Industry Corp. and Shanghai
Automotive Co. Limited. GM holds a 50 percent of the project.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
