<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Government Debt Expected to Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The total debt stock of the
Philippine government is expected to decline to 1.08 trillion
pesos (30.86 billion U.S. dollars) in 1998 from the 1.099 trillion
pesos (31.4 billion dollars) programmed debt for 1997.
</P>
<P>
Latest official documents show that the decline in the national
government's outstanding debt is assumed due to the slowdown in
both foreign and internally generated borrowings.
</P>
<P>
The drop in both sources of borrowing is foreseen because of
the additional revenues that will be raised from the full
implementation of the entire comprehensive tax reform program by
next year.
</P>
<P>
The Congress has approved the remaining portion of the tax
program, including the revenue yielding individual and corporate
taxation scheme and other revenue generating measures to be put in
place in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Total domestic debts of the national government is expected to
decline to 733.7 billion pesos (20.963 billion dollars) in 1998
from an estimated 734.5 billion pesos (20.986 billion dollars) in
1997, the data show.
</P>
<P>
Foreign liabilities of the national government is projected to
drop to 347 billion pesos (9.91 billion dollars) in 1998 from
364.8 billion projected (10.42 billion dollars) this year.
</P>
<P>
Domestic debt accounts for 67.89 percent of the estimated total
obligations of the national government for the period with
external debt representing the balance of 32.11 percent, according
to the data. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
