<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Foreign Currency Deposits Decrease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Philippine foreign currency
deposits slid 7.3 percent to 15.38 billion U.S. dollars as of
October 17 from the 16.6 billion dollars at the end of June this
year.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Central Bank Deputy Governor Alberto Reyes
attributed the drop to increased withdrawals following the
continued depreciation of the peso against the U.S. dollar and the
planned imposition of tax on these deposits.
</P>
<P>
Since July 11, when the peso started falling against the U.S.
dollar, the local currency has depreciated by 35.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the intervening period, foreign currency deposits
withdrawals totaled 1.42 billion dollars, or an average of 12.24
million a day, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted Reyes as saying that due to the depreciation
of the peso, investors tend to withdraw their dollars to take
advantage of the situation.
</P>
<P>
A plan by lawmakers to impose tax on interest income from
foreign currency deposits has triggered more jitters among dollar
account holders and prompted more withdrawals, according to the
reports.
</P>
<P>
The bulk or 80 percent of the foreign currency deposits are
held by residents such as exporters, importers and families of
overseas Filipino workers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
