<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Water Levels at Three Gorges Reservoir (10) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANDOUPING, (Three Gorges), November 3 (Xinhua) -- Three water
levels -- normal storage, flood stage and low level, are inherently
important to the future role the Three Gorges Reservoir will play
in flood control, power generation and navigation.
</P>
<P>
The normal water storage level refers to the depth of water in
the reservoir under normal operation. Higher than normal water
levels will prove the reservoir's greater flood control control,
power generation and navigation capabilities. However, higher
water levels will result in the inundation of more land, and will
require more investments, expanded resettlement of local residents
and proportional increases in negative impacts on the ecological
environment.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the normal water storage level of the reservoir
should be maintained at 175 meters, a level which would ensure a
water storage capacity of 39.3 billion cu.m.
</P>
<P>
The highest water level prior to flood season, or the flood
control water level, has been set at 145 meters. The water storage
capacity of 22.15 billion cu.m. allows leeway for the storage of
floodwaters.
</P>
<P>
The lowest water mark during the dry season fulfills
requirements for navigation and is set at a level of not lower
than 155 meters.
</P>
<P>
The adjusted water storage capacity is set at 16.5 billion
cu.m. at water levels of between 175-155 meters.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
