<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Says Goal Achieved in His U.S. Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang
Zemin said today that his state visit to the United States has
achieved the goal of bringing China-U.S. relations into a new
historical stage of development.
</P>
<P>
Jiang described, at a luncheon here, the goal of his nine-day
trip as "enhancing mutual understanding, broadening common ground,
developing cooperation and building a future together."
</P>
<P>
The luncheon was hosted by the Town Hall of Los Angeles, Asia
Society Southern California Center, National Committee on
U.S.-China Relations and U.S.-China People's Friendship
Association West Region Chapter.
</P>
<P>
And it was attended by about 600 guests, including former
U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the luncheon, which began with Chinese and
U.S. national anthems, California's governor Pete Wilson welcomed
Jiang to visit Los Angeles and California.
</P>
<P>
"Welcome to California -- the state built with Chinese muscle
in the 19th century and with Chinese genius in the high-tech world
in the 20th century," said Wilson, who highly praised the
contribution by Chinese immigrants to California's development.
</P>
<P>
"In the 21st century," Wilson noted, "the United States and
China hold the potential to be the world's largest trading
partners, sharing immense productive capacity and offering each
other vast and vary consumer markets."
</P>
<P>
"The enormous mutual benefit that can come from our
relationship of shared peace and prosperity requires on both sides
of the Pacific we make every effort to build that relationship,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"It will require open, constant and candid communication. When
we do have differences... we must build a relationship of the
understanding, the mutual respect and the trust that will be
required to resolve them," Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
In reply, Jiang summed up his current visit. "President Clinton
and I agreed that with a view to advancing the lofty cause of
promoting world peace and development, China and the United States
should strengthen cooperation and endeavor to build a constructive
strategic partnership oriented towards the 21st century."
</P>
<P>
"This is going to play a positive role in correctly handling
their differences in history, culture, social system and
development level," he said.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, who held the fifth summit with U.S. President Bill
Clinton on October 29, is scheduled to wind up his U.S. tour on
Monday. The state visit, the first since 1985, began on October 26.
</P>
<P>
Jiang told the guests at the luncheon that both China and the
United States hold that the two "should apply a strategic and
long-term perspective and take a firm hold of the overall
interests" in dealing with China-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
"The two sides stressed that we should further strengthen the
economic cooperation and trade on the basis of equality and mutual
benefit and expand the scale of the China-U.S. trade and
development," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Both also agreed that efforts should be made to "intensify the
exchanges between top leaders as well as government departments of
the two countries in order to facilitate timely exchange of views
and opinions on issues of common interest," he added.
</P>
<P>
A joint statement, issued after the summit on October 28, said
that a hot line will be established between Beijing and Washington.
</P>
<P>
Cabinet level officials of the two countries will have regular
consultations on political, security, arms control issues. There
will be more military cooperation. And they will start the
implementation of the China-U.S. Agreement on the Peaceful Uses of
Nuclear Energy.
</P>
<P>
Jiang also said both sides agreed the differences between the
two should be "handled properly in the spirit of mutual respect
and treating each other as equals through consultations on an
equal footing."
</P>
<P>
"The two sides should seek common ground while putting aside
their differences that can not be ironed out for the time being,
and should not take their differences in political system and
ideology as barriers to the growth of their relations," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles, in California on the U.S. west coast, is the last
leg of Jiang's U.S. tour. The second largest U.S. city and
Guangzhou, of China, became sister cities in 1981. China is the
second largest overseas trading partner of this U.S. city.
</P>
<P>
Last year, California's exports to China increased by 39
percent over the previous year and Chinese exports through
California ports totaled 21.1 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
