<HEADLINE> G-15 Summit Opens in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, November 3 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Group of 15
developing countries (G-15) began here today their seventh annual
summit to review the grouping's progress to chart its future
direction into the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
The three-day summit was opened by Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad.
</P>
<P>
Other leaders at the summit include Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe, Algerian President Liamine Zeroual, Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak, Indonesian President Soeharto, Peruvian President
Alberto Fujimori, Indian Vice President Krishan Kant, Argentine
Vice President Carlos Ruckauf and Jamaican Deputy Prime Minister
Seymour Mullings.
</P>
<P>
Senegal, Mexico and Brazil are represented by their foreign
ministers while Chile's economics minister and Venezuela's
industry and commerce minister are standing for their heads of
government.
</P>
<P>
The G-15 spans three continents and now comprises Algeria,
Argentina, Brazil, Chile, Egypt, India, Indonesia, Jamaica,
Malaysia, Mexico, Nigeria, Peru, Senegal, Venezuela and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
At the summit, Kenya will be admitted as the 16th member.
</P>
<P>
During the summit, the leaders will review the impact of
globalization on their developing economies and discuss measures
to step up trade, investment and technology cooperation, according
to official sources.
</P>
<P>
The leaders are set to issue a special statement on the
currency turmoil that has battered Southeast Asia including two
G-15 members, Malaysia and Indonesia, and triggered a meltdown of
stock markets from Hong Kong to Wall Street last week.
</P>
<P>
The statement to be issued at the end of the G-15 Summit will
present the G-15's collective views on the crisis and will also
include proposals on how to deal with the problem, Malaysian
Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said earlier.
</P>
<P>
The leaders are also expected to discuss the enhancement of
South-South dialogue apart from development cooperation, and to
boost intra-G-15 trade that stood at 72 billion U.S. dollars last
year as well as the promotion of North-South dialogue.
</P>
<P>
With a population of 1.74 billion and a combined trade volume
of 796 billion U.S. dollars or 7 percent of global trade last
year, the G-15 provides vast opportunities to be tapped by member
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
