<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Backgrounder: Three Gorges Reservoir Operational in Long Run (9) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANDOUPING, (Three Gorges), November 3 (Xinhua) -- The Three
Gorges Reservoir will replace ancient Yunmeng and Dongting lakes,
both prone to siltation, to store and manage the release of flood
waters of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
According to mathematical calculations by silt experts, the
reservoir should be able to accommodate 86 percent of anti-flood
storage and 92 percent of adjustable storage after 100 years of
operation. The calculations were based on no more reservoirs being
built on the upper reaches of the Yangtze River and the
worst-possible silting conditions.
</P>
<P>
However, a group of large reservoirs on the upper reaches on
the Yangtze River are on the agenda for construction before the
2030. Taking into account anti-silt measures in these reservoirs,
the silt deposited in the bottom of the reservoirs after one
century is equivalent to the amount piled up in four decades
without any measures being taken in the upper reaches.
</P>
<P>
The reason behind the reservoir's long operational period is
based on a method of "draining the muddy water while reserving the
clear water."
</P>
<P>
Generally, most floods and sediment pour into the reservoir in
the main flood season between July and September. The reservoir
will drain muddy water that carries huge amount of sand and gravel
in the flood season and save clear water in the dry season.
</P>
<P>
As a typical gorge reservoir, most silt deposits come from the
water rather than soil eroded from the shore. Also, the annual
runoff and flood peak discharge on the Yangtze at peak seasons are
much larger than the Yellow River, China's second longest, which
has serious soil erosion. The Yangtze usually carries much less
silt than the Yellow river.
</P>
<P>
All conditions appear to be beneficial for the Three Gorgers
Reservoir's ability to drain huge amounts of muddy water in flood
season while keeping sufficient storage for the dry season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0219 </DOCNO>
