<HEADLINE> Brazil's First Satellite-Deployment Rocket Destroyed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's first space rocket
was destroyed and fell into the seas today soon after its launch,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
The rocket was launched at 10:25 a.m. local time (1225 GMT) but
was destroyed 65 seconds later by remote control at an altitude of
3,230 meters because one of its propulsion engines failed to
ignite, the Globo television reported.
</P>
<P>
Debris of the Brazilian-made Satellite Launch Vehicle (VLS)
rocket plunged into the sea some two kilometers from the Alcantara
space station, in northeastern Maranahao state.
</P>
<P>
The rocket, with a cost of about 6.5 million U.S. dollars, was
scheduled to carry the country's Data Gathering Satellite into
Earth's Orbit to collect environmental and agricultural data.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian space agency officials said Brazil will go ahead with
scheduled launches in each of the next three years and that of the
1998's would probably come in September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
