<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Runner Wins Women's Title at New York Marathon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, November 2 (Xinhua) -- Veteran Swiss Runner
Franziska Rochat-Moser completed the 42.195 kilometers course at
2:28:42 in the 28th New York City Marathon here today to take the
women's title.
</P>
<P>
A lawyer by profession, 31-year-old Rochat-Moser is a national
record holder with 2:27:44 set in the 1994 Frankfurt Marathon.
</P>
<P>
She ran 2:29:35 to finish fourth in the 1995 Boston Marathon,
and was sixth in Boston last year in 2:31:33.
</P>
<P>
She is a two time Olympian and participant of three World
Championships with an 18th place in the 1996 Olympic Marathon and
eighth (2:36:16) in the 1997 World Championships Marathon.
</P>
<P>
The runner-up in the NYC event today is South Africa's Colleen
de Reuck who was born on April 13, 1964.
</P>
<P>
A career runner too, de Reuck made a breakthrough in the
marathon last year, winning at Berlin in 2:26:35, the fourth
fastest time of 1996 and almost a five-minute improvement over
her prior fastest time of 2:31:21 in 1992.
</P>
<P>
She followed that with a third-place finish in 2:28:03 at the
1997 Boston Marathon, where she finished a place ahead of
three-time winner Uta Pippig.
</P>
<P>
A two time Olympian, she has a half-marathon best of 1:08:39.
</P>
<P>
Franca Fiacconi of Italy finished third in the 28th NYC
Marathon in 2:30:15. Her personal best of 2:28:22 was set at the
previous NYC Marathon, the second finish in the event.
</P>
<P>
Born in Rome on October 14, 1965, Fiacconi entered the 1996
NYC Marathon just 21 days after winning the Carpi Marathon in a
career-best of 2:28:42. She finished this year's Carpi in
2:28:51, just eight seconds behind countrywoman and fellow NYC
Marathon entrant Ornella Ferrara, who placed fifth today with
2:31:44.
</P>
<P>
Fiacconi won four straight marathons in 1994 and 1995, with a
2:30:10 win in the 1995 Cesano Boscone Marathon in Italy.
</P>
<P>
She won the 1996 Turin Marathon in 2:29:18 and placed 13th in
the 1997 World Championships Marathon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
