<DOCNO> XIE19971103.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-11-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan, Swiss Runners Snatch 1997 NYC Marathon Titles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, November 2 (Xinhua) -- John Kagwe from Kenya crossed
the finish line first at the New York City Marathon here on a
misty Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Kagwe's winning time of 2:08:11 was the second fastest time in
the race's 28-year history.
</P>
<P>
"This is a dream (which) come true for me," said the
28-year-old African runner. He said he won because he used
better tactics this year.
</P>
<P>
Franziska Rochat-Moser, a lawyer from Switzerland, won the
women's race in 2:28:42.
</P>
<P>
The New York Marathon this year followed the same route and
time schedule of the previous ones, but it started in
intermittent drizzles. Some 30,000 runneres surged across the
Verrazano-Narrows Bridge in the city's southwest at the sound of
the starting cannon at 10:35 a.m. Local residents braved the
drizzle, giving their support by shouting to the runners behind
the police brocades.
</P>
<P>
Kagwe has been participating the race and kept improving his
records for the past few years. He was the fifth in the 1995 NYC
Marathon and fourth here last year in 2:10:59.
</P>
<P>
At the finishing line of the Central Park, Manhattan, Kagwe
said his shoe laces got loosened three times at third mile, 10th
mile and about 23th mile respectively. He tightened the first
two, but ignored the last one and ran through the remaining miles
with the loosen laces. "I knew I could not win if I fixed my
laces again this time," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kagwe said he was too eager to win last year, but did not
succeed. This time he was very patient and followed the first
few fastest runners, including his countryman Kenneth Cheruyot,
who kept the leading position for the first 17 miles.
</P>
<P>
The results of men's race showed that Cheruyot was not among
the first ten.
</P>
<P>
"When has anyone in the recent past won from running alone in
front?" said Tom Fleming, who has twice won the NYC Marathon in
1974 and 1975, and is now a radio commentator.
</P>
<P>
"Winners and record-setters usually run even pace or negative
splits," he said.
</P>
<P>
Fellow Kenyan Joseph Chebet came in second at 2:09:27 and
Italian Stefano Baldini was third with a time of 2:09:31.
</P>
<P>
Kagwe won 50,000 U.S. dollars plus a time bonus of 40,000
U.S. dollars and a Kia Sportage automobile.
</P>
<P>
Rochat-Moser, 31, is also the Swiss record holder. She became
the leader at about 20th mile where, she said later, she could
found only male runners around. Rochat-Moser is a lawyer at his
hometown of Crissier, near Lausanne. She is a two-time Olympian
and a veteran of three World Championships. But she took part in
the New York race for the first time.
</P>
<P>
"I was really surprised. I knew I was in good shape,"
Rochat-Moser said.
</P>
<P>
The second finisher was South Africa's Coolleen deReuck, who
ended up at 2:29:11, and Italian Franca Fiacconi covered the
distance at 2:30:15 to take third place.
</P>
<P>
More than 8,800 women were among the 30,000 runners registered
for the 28th New York City Marathon, which passes through all to
the city's five boroughs.
</P>
<P>
The oldese competitors this year was 90-year-old Sam Gadless,
who ran his first New York City Marathon in 1992 and was running
Sunday with his 55-year-old son and his 25-year-old grandson.
</P>
<P>
While the men's winning time was just 11 seconds off the race
record, the women's results were well off the record of 2:24:40
set by Lisa Ondieki of Australia in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
