<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, November 3 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers published today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- A 60 million U.S. dollar anti-drug strategy announced
yesterday by Prime Minister John Howard will boost law
enforcement, introduce zero tolerance of illegal substances in
schools and direct more funds to frontline drug treatment in
Australia.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- An Australian government agency put forward a proposal for
the establishment of an air link with the Antarctic, the phasing
out of up to two of Australia's three bases and the possibility of
a summer base for tourists in a report on the country's 50-year
history of Antarctic research expeditions.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- Most Australians can no longer afford the cost of legal
cases in the Family Court that decide who gets the family home or
custody of children after divorce as a dispute over an ordinary
home can cost about 5,600 to 7,000 U.S. dollars for a one-day
hearing.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- Australian financial markets face more turbulence this week,
with the Reserve Bank meeting to decide the future of local
interest rates and analysts tipping further falls in the key U.S.
and Asian share markets.  
</P>
